{"title_page": "1978 FIFA World Cup Group A", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n'''Group A of the 1978 FIFA World Cup''' was one of two groups of nations competing for the [[De facto]] semifinals  the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]. The group's first round of matches began on 14 June and its last matches were played on 21 June. All six group matches were played either at the [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]] in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], or the [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]] in the capital [[Buenos Aires]]. The group consisted of [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] (the Defending Champions) as well as the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] (the former runners up), [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and [[Austria national football team|Austria]]. The Netherlands advanced to the final match, and Italy advanced to the third place match.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup Guide - 1978 Argentina |url=http://www.worldcupbrazil.net/world-cup-history/world-cup-70s-90s/1978-argentina/|work=worldcupbrazil.net|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Qualified teams==\nThe winners of Group 1 and 3 and the runners-up of Group 2 and 4 qualified for Group A of the second round.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Group\n! width=\"150\" | Winners\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 1|1]]\n| {{fb|ITA|1946}}\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 3|3]]\n| {{fb|AUT}}\n|-\n! Group\n! width=\"150\" | Runners-up\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 2|2]]\n| {{fb|FRG}}\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 4|4]]\n| {{fb|NED}}\n|}\n\n==Standings==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WDL\n|teamwidth=180\n\n|update=complete \n|winpoints=2\n|source=[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/groups/index.html FIFA]\n\n|team1=NED |team2=ITA |team3=FRG |team4=AUT\n|result1=F |result2=TP\n\n|win_NED=2 |draw_NED=1 |loss_NED=0 |gf_NED=9 |ga_NED=4\n|win_ITA=1 |draw_ITA=1 |loss_ITA=1 |gf_ITA=2 |ga_ITA=2\n|win_FRG=0 |draw_FRG=2 |loss_FRG=1 |gf_FRG=4 |ga_FRG=5\n|win_AUT=1 |draw_AUT=0 |loss_AUT=2 |gf_AUT=4 |ga_AUT=8\n\n|name_FRG={{fb|FRG}}\n|name_ITA={{fb|ITA|1946}}\n|name_NED={{fb|NED}}\n|name_AUT={{fb|AUT}}\n\n|res_col_header=Q\n|col_F=green1 |text_F=Advance to [[1978 FIFA World Cup#Final|final]]\n\n|col_TP=blue1 |text_TP=Advance to [[1978 FIFA World Cup#Third place play-off|third place play-off]]\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Matches==\n\n===Austria vs Netherlands===\nAfter an unconvincing group stage performance the Netherlands knew they had to play better if they were to qualify for the finals, and took on surprise qualifiers Austria in their first game. They started well when an unmarked [[Ernie Brandts]] headed in [[Arie Haan]]'s free kick. The Dutch then won a penalty kick after [[Gerhard Breitenberger (footballer, born 1954)|Gerhard Breitenberger]] fouled [[Wim Jansen]] and [[Rob Rensenbrink]] neatly scored. Rensenbrink then took advantage of some poor defending to provide assist for [[Johnny Rep]] to score on either side of half time. Austria which created several chances and were unlucky to score in the first half got one back in the eightieth minute when defender [[Erich Obermayer]] scored a brilliant lob over the Dutch goalkeeper for a goal. The Dutch weren't to be deterred as Rensenbrink provided yet another assist this time [[Willy van de Kerkhof]] to score just two minutes later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria - Netherlands Match Report |url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1978/ph2gr1_hol_v_aut.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup History: Argentina 1978|url=http://www.sportal.com.au/football/world-cup-2014/world-cup-history-argentina-1978/8ryb0kgibwe0zzhi3z2urkxb|work=Sportal|accessdate=6 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714225832/http://www.sportal.com.au/football/world-cup-2014/world-cup-history-argentina-1978/8ryb0kgibwe0zzhi3z2urkxb|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{football box\n|date = 14 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|AUT}}\n|score = 1\u20135\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2220\n|team2 = {{fb|NED}}\n|goals1 = [[Erich Obermayer|Obermayer]] {{goal|80}}\n|goals2 = [[Ernie Brandts|Brandts]] {{goal|6}}<br />[[Rob Rensenbrink|Rensenbrink]] {{goal|35|pen.}}<br />[[Johnny Rep|Rep]] {{goal|36||53}}<br />[[Willy van de Kerkhof|W. van de Kerkhof]] {{goal|82}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance = 25,050\n|referee = [[John Gordon (referee)|John Gordon]] ([[Scottish Football Association|Scotland]]) }}\n\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n|pattern_la = _blackshoulders\n|pattern_b  = _shoulder_stripes_black_stripes_collar\n|pattern_ra = _blackshoulders\n|pattern_sh = _black_thinstripe_color\n|pattern_so = _redtop\n|leftarm    = FFFFFF\n|body       = FFFFFF\n|rightarm   = FFFFFF\n|shorts     = FFFFFF\n|socks      = 000000\n|title      = Austria\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _netherlands80h\n| pattern_b  = _netherlands80h\n| pattern_ra = _netherlands80h\n| pattern_sh = _netherlands1985h\n| pattern_so  = _netherlands80h\n| leftarm    = FFFFFF\n| body       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm   = FFFFFF\n| shorts     = FF5900\n| socks      = FF6000\n| title      = Netherlands\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Friedl Koncilia]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Robert Sara]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3'''|| [[Erich Obermayer]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Gerhard Breitenberger (footballer, born 1954)|Gerhard Breitenberger]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Bruno Pezzey]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Josef Hickersberger]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' || [[Herbert Prohaska]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''11''' || [[Kurt Jara]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''12''' || [[Eduard Krieger]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Hans Krankl]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''|| [[Wilhelm Kreuz]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Senekowitsch]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Piet Schrijvers]]\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Jan Poortvliet]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Ruud Krol]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''7''' || [[Piet Wildschut]]\n|-\n|DF || '''22''' || [[Ernie Brandts]] || || {{suboff|66}}\n|-\n|MF || '''6''' || [[Wim Jansen]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Arie Haan]]\n|-\n|MF|| '''10''' || [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]] || || {{suboff|60}}\n|-\n|MF || '''11''' || [[Willy van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|FW || '''16''' || [[Johnny Rep]]\n|-\n|FW || '''12''' || [[Rob Rensenbrink]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF|| '''3''' || [[Dick Schoenaker]] || || {{subon|60}}\n|-\n|DF|| '''4''' || [[Adrie van Kraay]] || || {{subon|66}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|- \n|colspan=4|{{Flagicon|AUT}} [[Ernst Happel]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Italy vs West Germany===\n{{see also|Germany\u2013Italy football rivalry}}\n\n{{football box\n|date = 14 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 0\u20130\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2349\n|team2 = {{fb|FRG}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]], Buenos Aires\n|attendance = 67,547\n|referee = [[Du\u0161an Maksimovi\u0107]] ([[Football Association of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Mauro Bellugi]]\n|-\n|DF || '''3''' || [[Antonio Cabrini]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Claudio Gentile]]\n|-\n|DF || '''8''' || [[Gaetano Scirea]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Giancarlo Antognoni]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|MF || '''10''' || [[Romeo Benetti]]\n|-\n|MF || '''14''' || [[Marco Tardelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''16''' || [[Franco Causio]]\n|-\n|CF || '''18''' || [[Roberto Bettega]]\n|-\n|CF || '''21''' || [[Paolo Rossi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF || '''15''' || [[Renato Zaccarelli]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Sepp Maier]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Berti Vogts]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Bernard Dietz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Rolf R\u00fcssmann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Manfred Kaltz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''8''' ||[[Herbert Zimmermann (footballer)|Herbert Zimmerman]] || || {{suboff|53}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Rainer Bonhof]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10''' || [[Heinz Flohe]] || || {{suboff|68}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''17''' || [[Bernd Hoelzenbein]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Klaus Fischer]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitute:'''\n|-\n|DF ||'''13''' || [[Harald Konopka]] || {{subon|53}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''15''' || [[Erich Beer]] || {{subon|68}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Schoen]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Netherlands vs West Germany===\n{{see also|Germany\u2013Netherlands football rivalry}}\n\nThis highly anticipated match was a repeat of the [[1974 FIFA World Cup Final]], with the Netherlands fielding six players who had played that day and West Germany four. The match official [[Ram\u00f3n Barreto]] of Uruguay coincidentally had also been one of the linesmen at the 1974 final.\n\nThe 1974 final has started with the Dutch scoring within a two minutes, and in this game there was another early goal although it went the German's way. The Dutch goaltender [[Piet Schrijvers]] could only parry [[Rainer Bonhof]]'s free kick right into the path of [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik]] who headed home. The Netherlands equalized around the thirty-minute mark when [[Arie Haan]] let fly from 35 yards and into the top corner.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/WGermany.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716205213/http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/WGermany.htm |archive-date=16 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKnowing a draw would be enough Netherlands refrained from taking chances in the second half. Against the run of play West Germany were awarded a soft free-kick, the Dutch were complaining with the referee and did not keep their concentration [[Erich Beer]] crossed for [[Dieter M\u00fcller]] to power in a header. The goal gave the Netherlands the momentum to score though and eight minutes from time [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]] took a pass from his twin brother [[Willy van de Kerkhof|Willy]], cut inside a defender and smashed home. There would be a few more chances as [[Johnny Rep]] hit the woodwork and Schrijvers was forced to save from Beer.\n\nThe end of the game ended in bizarre fashion, with substitute [[Dick Nanninga]] shown a yellow card for an off the ball incident and then seconds later referee Barreto showed the same player a red card for apparently laughing at the decision to give him a card. It took five minutes to restore order on the field as the bewildered Nanninga was led off.\n\n{{football box\n|date = 18 June 1978\n|time = 16:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|NED}}\n|score = 2\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2348\n|team2 = {{fb|FRG}}\n|goals1 = [[Arie Haan|Haan]] {{goal|27}}<br />[[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof|R. van de Kerkhof]] {{goal|82}}\n|goals2 = [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik|Abramczik]] {{goal|3}}<br />[[Dieter M\u00fcller|D. M\u00fcller]] {{goal|70}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance = 40,750\n|referee = [[Ram\u00f3n Barreto]] ([[Asociaci\u00f3n Uruguaya de F\u00fatbol|Uruguay]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Piet Schrijvers]]\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Jan Poortvliet]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Ruud Krol]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''7''' || [[Piet Wildschut]] || || {{suboff|79}}\n|-\n|DF || '''22''' || [[Ernie Brandts]]\n|-\n|MF || '''6''' || [[Wim Jansen]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Arie Haan]]\n|-\n|MF|| '''10''' || [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|MF || '''11''' || [[Willy van de Kerkhof]] || {{yel|6}}\n|-\n|FW || '''16''' || [[Johnny Rep]]\n|-\n|FW || '''12''' || [[Rob Rensenbrink]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|FW|| '''18''' || [[Dick Nanninga]] || {{sent off|1|87|88}} || {{subon|79}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|- \n|colspan=4|{{Flagicon|AUT}} [[Ernst Happel]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Sepp Maier]] || {{yel|84}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Berti Vogts]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Bernard Dietz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Rolf R\u00fcssmann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Manfred Kaltz]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Rainer Bonhof]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''|| [[Erich Beer]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''17'''|| [[Bernd H\u00f6lzenbein]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' || [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''14''' || [[Dieter M\u00fcller]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Sch\u00f6n]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Italy vs Austria===\n\n{{football box\n|date = 18 June 1978\n|time = 16:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 1\u20130\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2221\n|team2 = {{fb|AUT}}\n|goals1 = [[Paolo Rossi|Rossi]] {{goal|13}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]], Buenos Aires\n|attendance = 66,695\n|referee = [[Francis Rion]] ([[Royal Belgian Football Association|Belgium]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Mauro Bellugi]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|DF || '''3''' || [[Antonio Cabrini]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Claudio Gentile]]\n|-\n|DF || '''8''' || [[Gaetano Scirea]]\n|-\n|MF || '''10''' || [[Romeo Benetti]]\n|-\n|MF || '''14''' || [[Marco Tardelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''15''' || [[Renato Zaccarelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''16''' || [[Franco Causio]]\n|-\n|CF || '''18''' || [[Roberto Bettega]] || || {{suboff|72}}\n|-\n|CF || '''21''' || [[Paolo Rossi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF || '''4''' || [[Antonello Cuccureddu]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|FW || '''19''' || [[Francesco Graziani]] || || {{subon|72}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Friedl Koncilia]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Robert Sara]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Erich Obermayer]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Bruno Pezzey]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''14''' || [[Heinrich Strasser]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Josef Hickersberger]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' || [[Herbert Prohaska]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''12''' || [[Eduard Krieger]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Hans Krankl]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10''' || [[Wilhelm Kreuz]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''18''' || [[Walter Schachner]] || || {{suboff|63}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|FW ||'''19''' || [[Hans Pirkner]] || || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Senekowitsch]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Austria vs West Germany===\n{{main|Austria v West Germany (1978 FIFA World Cup)}}\n{{football box\n|date = 21 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|AUT}}\n|score = 3\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2217\n|team2 = {{fb|FRG}}\n|goals1 = [[Berti Vogts|Vogts]] {{goal|59|o.g.}}<br />[[Hans Krankl|Krankl]] {{goal|66||87}}\n|goals2 = [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge|Rummenigge]] {{goal|19}}<br />[[Bernd H\u00f6lzenbein|H\u00f6lzenbein]] {{goal|72}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance = 38,318\n|referee = [[Abraham Klein (referee)|Abraham Klein]] ([[Israel Football Association|Israel]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Friedl Koncilia]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Robert Sara]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|85}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Erich Obermayer]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Bruno Pezzey]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''14''' || [[Heinrich Strasser]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Josef Hickersberger]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' || [[Herbert Prohaska]] || {{yel|69}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''12''' || [[Eduard Krieger]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Hans Krankl]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10''' || [[Wilhelm Kreuz]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''18''' || [[Walter Schachner]] || || {{suboff|71}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|FW ||'''17''' || [[Franz Oberacher]] || || {{subon|71}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Senekowitsch]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Sepp Maier]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Berti Vogts]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Bernard Dietz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Rolf R\u00fcssmann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Manfred Kaltz]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Rainer Bonhof]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15''' || [[Erich Beer]] || || {{suboff|45}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''17'''|| [[Bernd H\u00f6lzenbein]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' || [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik]] || {{yel|69}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''14''' || [[Dieter M\u00fcller]] || || {{suboff|60}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitute:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''20''' || [[Hansi M\u00fcller]] || || {{subon|45}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Klaus Fischer]] || || {{subon|60}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Sch\u00f6n]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Italy vs Netherlands===\nThis match was a semifinal in all but name with the winner being assured a place in the final, although the Netherlands could advance with a draw and a Germany draw or loss. Italy started the positive and scored when [[Ernie Brandts]] in an attempt to stop [[Roberto Bettega]] only succeeded in putting the ball into his own net. The goal would have consequences for the Netherlands as [[Piet Schrijvers]] was injured on the play and had to be stretchered off for [[Jan Jongbloed]]. Italy dominated the remainder of the first half. In a physical match [[Johnny Rep]] was cautioned for fouling [[Romeo Benetti]], who was later to pick up a yellow card himself for fouling Rensenbrink, meaning the Italian defender would miss the match should Italy reach it. Early in the second half [[Arie Haan]] was cautioned for a challenge on [[Marco Tardelli]] who later also picked up a yellow card meaning he too would miss Italy's next match. Some felt that [[Antonio Cabrini]]'s challenge on Haan many felt warranted a red card, not just a yellow. Shortly after half time Brandts, who earlier scored an own goal blasted home a shot to equalizes. Than fourteen minutes from time Haan hit an audacious shot 30 yards out that went off Zoff's left post an into the net.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/Italy.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=6 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622075829/http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/Italy.htm |archive-date=22 June 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n{{football box\n|date = 21 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 1\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2391\n|team2 = {{fb|NED}}\n|goals1 = [[Ernie Brandts|Brandts]] {{goal|19|o.g.}}\n|goals2 = [[Ernie Brandts|Brandts]] {{goal|49}}<br />[[Arie Haan|Haan]] {{goal|76}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]], Buenos Aires\n|attendance = 67,433\n|referee = [[Angel Franco Mart\u00ednez]] ([[Royal Spanish Football Federation|Spain]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''3''' || [[Antonio Cabrini]] || {{yel|65}}\n|-\n|DF || '''4''' || [[Antonello Cuccureddu]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Claudio Gentile]]\n|-\n|DF || '''8''' || [[Gaetano Scirea]]\n|-\n|MF || '''10''' || [[Romeo Benetti]] || {{yel|40}} || {{suboff|77}}\n|-\n|MF || '''14''' || [[Marco Tardelli]] || {{yel|70}}\n|-\n|MF || '''15''' || [[Renato Zaccarelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''16''' || [[Franco Causio]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|CF || '''18''' || [[Roberto Bettega]]\n|-\n|CF || '''21''' || [[Paolo Rossi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF || '''17''' || [[Claudio Sala]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|FW || '''19''' || [[Francesco Graziani]] || || {{subon|72}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Piet Schrijvers]] || || {{suboff|21}}\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Jan Poortvliet]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Ruud Krol]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''6''' || [[Wim Jansen]]\n|-\n|DF || '''22''' || [[Ernie Brandts]]\n|-\n|MF || '''13''' || [[Johan Neeskens]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Arie Haan]] || {{yel|50}}\n|-\n|MF|| '''10''' || [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|MF || '''11''' || [[Willy van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|FW || '''16''' || [[Johnny Rep]] || {{yel|35}} || {{suboff|65}}\n|-\n|FW || '''12''' || [[Rob Rensenbrink]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|GK|| '''8''' || [[Jan Jongbloed]] || || {{subon|21}}\n|-\n|DF|| '''4''' || [[Adrie van Kraay]] || || {{subon|65}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|- \n|colspan=4|{{Flagicon|AUT}} [[Ernst Happel]]\n|}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1978 FIFA World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World}}\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup|Groups]]\n[[Category:West Germany at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|G]]\n[[Category:Italy at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|Group]]\n[[Category:Austria at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|Group]]\n[[Category:Netherlands at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|Group]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n'''Group A of the 1978 FIFA World Cup''' was one of two groups of nations competing for the [[De facto]] semifinals  the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]. The group's first round of matches began on 14 June and its last matches were played on 21 June. All six group matches were played either at the [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]] in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], or the [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]] in the capital [[Buenos Aires]]. The group consisted of [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] (the Defending Champions) as well as the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] (the former runners up), [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and [[Austria national football team|Austria]]. The Netherlands advanced to the final match, and Italy advanced to the third place match.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup Guide - 1978 Argentina |url=http://www.worldcupbrazil.net/world-cup-history/world-cup-70s-90s/1978-argentina/|work=worldcupbrazil.net|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Qualified teams==\nThe winners of Group 1 and 3 and the runners-up of Group 2 and 4 qualified for Group A of the second round.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Group\n! width=\"150\" | Winners\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 1|1]]\n| {{fb|ITA|1946}}\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 3|3]]\n| {{fb|AUT}}\n|-\n! Group\n! width=\"150\" | Runners-up\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 2|2]]\n| {{fb|FRG}}\n|-\n! [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 4|4]]\n| {{fb|NED}}\n|}\n\n==Standings==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WDL\n|teamwidth=180\n\n|update=complete \n|winpoints=2\n|source=[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/groups/index.html FIFA]\n\n|team1=NED |team2=ITA |team3=FRG |team4=AUT\n|result1=F |result2=TP\n\n|win_NED=2 |draw_NED=1 |loss_NED=0 |gf_NED=9 |ga_NED=4\n|win_ITA=1 |draw_ITA=1 |loss_ITA=1 |gf_ITA=2 |ga_ITA=2\n|win_FRG=0 |draw_FRG=2 |loss_FRG=1 |gf_FRG=4 |ga_FRG=5\n|win_AUT=1 |draw_AUT=0 |loss_AUT=2 |gf_AUT=4 |ga_AUT=8\n\n|name_FRG={{fb|FRG}}\n|name_ITA={{fb|ITA|1946}}\n|name_NED={{fb|NED}}\n|name_AUT={{fb|AUT}}\n\n|res_col_header=Q\n|col_F=green1 |text_F=Advance to [[1978 FIFA World Cup#Final|final]]\n\n|col_TP=blue1 |text_TP=Advance to [[1978 FIFA World Cup#Third place play-off|third place play-off]]\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Matches==\n\n===Austria vs Netherlands===\nAfter an unconvincing group stage performance the Netherlands knew they had to play better if they were to qualify for the finals, and took on surprise qualifiers Austria in their first game. They started well when an unmarked [[Ernie Brandts]] headed in [[Arie Haan]]'s free kick. The Dutch then won a penalty kick after [[Gerhard Breitenberger (footballer, born 1954)|Gerhard Breitenberger]] fouled [[Wim Jansen]] and [[Rob Rensenbrink]] neatly scored. Rensenbrink then took advantage of some poor defending to provide assist for [[Johnny Rep]] to score on either side of half time. Austria which created several chances and were unlucky to score in the first half got one back in the eightieth minute when defender [[Erich Obermayer]] scored a brilliant lob over the Dutch goalkeeper for a goal. The Dutch weren't to be deterred as Rensenbrink provided yet another assist this time [[Willy van de Kerkhof]] to score just two minutes later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria - Netherlands Match Report |url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1978/ph2gr1_hol_v_aut.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup History: Argentina 1978|url=http://www.sportal.com.au/football/world-cup-2014/world-cup-history-argentina-1978/8ryb0kgibwe0zzhi3z2urkxb|work=Sportal|accessdate=6 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714225832/http://www.sportal.com.au/football/world-cup-2014/world-cup-history-argentina-1978/8ryb0kgibwe0zzhi3z2urkxb|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{football box\n|date = 14 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|AUT}}\n|score = 1\u20135\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2220\n|team2 = {{fb|NED}}\n|goals1 = [[Erich Obermayer|Obermayer]] {{goal|80}}\n|goals2 = [[Ernie Brandts|Brandts]] {{goal|6}}<br />[[Rob Rensenbrink|Rensenbrink]] {{goal|35|pen.}}<br />[[Johnny Rep|Rep]] {{goal|36||53}}<br />[[Willy van de Kerkhof|W. van de Kerkhof]] {{goal|82}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance = 25,050\n|referee = [[John Gordon (referee)|John Gordon]] ([[Scottish Football Association|Scotland]]) }}\n\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n|pattern_la = _blackshoulders\n|pattern_b  = _shoulder_stripes_black_stripes_collar\n|pattern_ra = _blackshoulders\n|pattern_sh = _black_thinstripe_color\n|pattern_so = _redtop\n|leftarm    = FFFFFF\n|body       = FFFFFF\n|rightarm   = FFFFFF\n|shorts     = FFFFFF\n|socks      = 000000\n|title      = Austria\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _netherlands80h\n| pattern_b  = _netherlands80h\n| pattern_ra = _netherlands80h\n| pattern_sh = _netherlands1985h\n| pattern_so  = _netherlands80h\n| leftarm    = FFFFFF\n| body       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm   = FFFFFF\n| shorts     = FF5900\n| socks      = FF6000\n| title      = Netherlands\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Friedl Koncilia]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Robert Sara]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3'''|| [[Erich Obermayer]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Gerhard Breitenberger (footballer, born 1954)|Gerhard Breitenberger]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Bruno Pezzey]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Josef Hickersberger]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' || [[Herbert Prohaska]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''11''' || [[Kurt Jara]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''12''' || [[Eduard Krieger]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Hans Krankl]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''|| [[Wilhelm Kreuz]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Senekowitsch]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Piet Schrijvers]]\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Jan Poortvliet]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Ruud Krol]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''7''' || [[Piet Wildschut]]\n|-\n|DF || '''22''' || [[Ernie Brandts]] || || {{suboff|66}}\n|-\n|MF || '''6''' || [[Wim Jansen]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Arie Haan]]\n|-\n|MF|| '''10''' || [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]] || || {{suboff|60}}\n|-\n|MF || '''11''' || [[Willy van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|FW || '''16''' || [[Johnny Rep]]\n|-\n|FW || '''12''' || [[Rob Rensenbrink]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF|| '''3''' || [[Dick Schoenaker]] || || {{subon|60}}\n|-\n|DF|| '''4''' || [[Adrie van Kraay]] || || {{subon|66}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|- \n|colspan=4|{{Flagicon|AUT}} [[Ernst Happel]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Italy vs West Germany===\n{{see also|Germany\u2013Italy football rivalry}}\n\n{{football box\n|date = 14 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 0\u20130\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2349\n|team2 = {{fb|FRG}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]], Buenos Aires\n|attendance = 67,547\n|referee = [[Du\u0161an Maksimovi\u0107]] ([[Football Association of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Mauro Bellugi]]\n|-\n|DF || '''3''' || [[Antonio Cabrini]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Claudio Gentile]]\n|-\n|DF || '''8''' || [[Gaetano Scirea]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Giancarlo Antognoni]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|MF || '''10''' || [[Romeo Benetti]]\n|-\n|MF || '''14''' || [[Marco Tardelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''16''' || [[Franco Causio]]\n|-\n|CF || '''18''' || [[Roberto Bettega]]\n|-\n|CF || '''21''' || [[Paolo Rossi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF || '''15''' || [[Renato Zaccarelli]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Sepp Maier]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Berti Vogts]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Bernard Dietz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Rolf R\u00fcssmann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Manfred Kaltz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''8''' ||[[Herbert Zimmermann (footballer)|Herbert Zimmerman]] || || {{suboff|53}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Rainer Bonhof]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10''' || [[Heinz Flohe]] || || {{suboff|68}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''17''' || [[Bernd Hoelzenbein]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Klaus Fischer]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitute:'''\n|-\n|DF ||'''13''' || [[Harald Konopka]] || {{subon|53}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''15''' || [[Erich Beer]] || {{subon|68}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Schoen]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Netherlands vs West Germany===\n{{see also|Germany\u2013Netherlands football rivalry}}\n\nThis highly anticipated match was a repeat of the [[1974 FIFA World Cup Final]], with the Netherlands fielding six players who had played that day and West Germany four. The match official [[Ram\u00f3n Barreto]] of Uruguay coincidentally had also been one of the linesmen at the 1974 final.\n\nThe 1974 final has started with the Dutch scoring within a two minutes, and in this game there was another early goal although it went the German's way. The Dutch goaltender [[Piet Schrijvers]] could only parry [[Rainer Bonhof]]'s free kick right into the path of [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik]] who headed home. The Netherlands equalized around the thirty-minute mark when [[Arie Haan]] let fly from 35 yards and into the top corner.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/WGermany.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716205213/http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/WGermany.htm |archive-date=16 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKnowing a draw would be enough Netherlands refrained from taking chances in the second half. Against the run of play West Germany were awarded a soft free-kick, the Dutch were complaining with the referee and did not keep their concentration [[Erich Beer]] crossed for [[Dieter M\u00fcller]] to power in a header. The goal gave the Netherlands the momentum to score though and eight minutes from time [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]] took a pass from his twin brother [[Willy van de Kerkhof|Willy]], cut inside a defender and smashed home. There would be a few more chances as [[Johnny Rep]] hit the woodwork and Schrijvers was forced to save from Beer.\n\nThe end of the game ended in bizarre fashion, with substitute [[Dick Nanninga]] shown a yellow card for an off the ball incident and then seconds later referee Barreto showed the same player a red card for apparently laughing at the decision to give him a card. It took five minutes to restore order on the field as the bewildered Nanninga was led off.\n\n{{football box\n|date = 18 June 1978\n|time = 16:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|NED}}\n|score = 2\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2348\n|team2 = {{fb|FRG}}\n|goals1 = [[Arie Haan|Haan]] {{goal|27}}<br />[[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof|R. van de Kerkhof]] {{goal|82}}\n|goals2 = [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik|Abramczik]] {{goal|3}}<br />[[Dieter M\u00fcller|D. M\u00fcller]] {{goal|70}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance = 40,750\n|referee = [[Ram\u00f3n Barreto]] ([[Asociaci\u00f3n Uruguaya de F\u00fatbol|Uruguay]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Piet Schrijvers]]\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Jan Poortvliet]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Ruud Krol]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''7''' || [[Piet Wildschut]] || || {{suboff|79}}\n|-\n|DF || '''22''' || [[Ernie Brandts]]\n|-\n|MF || '''6''' || [[Wim Jansen]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Arie Haan]]\n|-\n|MF|| '''10''' || [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|MF || '''11''' || [[Willy van de Kerkhof]] || {{yel|6}}\n|-\n|FW || '''16''' || [[Johnny Rep]]\n|-\n|FW || '''12''' || [[Rob Rensenbrink]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|FW|| '''18''' || [[Dick Nanninga]] || {{sent off|1|87|88}} || {{subon|79}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|- \n|colspan=4|{{Flagicon|AUT}} [[Ernst Happel]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Sepp Maier]] || {{yel|84}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Berti Vogts]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Bernard Dietz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Rolf R\u00fcssmann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Manfred Kaltz]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Rainer Bonhof]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''|| [[Erich Beer]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''17'''|| [[Bernd H\u00f6lzenbein]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' || [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''14''' || [[Dieter M\u00fcller]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Sch\u00f6n]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Italy vs Austria===\n\n{{football box\n|date = 18 June 1978\n|time = 16:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 1\u20130\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2221\n|team2 = {{fb|AUT}}\n|goals1 = [[Paolo Rossi|Rossi]] {{goal|13}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]], Buenos Aires\n|attendance = 66,695\n|referee = [[Francis Rion]] ([[Royal Belgian Football Association|Belgium]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Mauro Bellugi]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|DF || '''3''' || [[Antonio Cabrini]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Claudio Gentile]]\n|-\n|DF || '''8''' || [[Gaetano Scirea]]\n|-\n|MF || '''10''' || [[Romeo Benetti]]\n|-\n|MF || '''14''' || [[Marco Tardelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''15''' || [[Renato Zaccarelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''16''' || [[Franco Causio]]\n|-\n|CF || '''18''' || [[Roberto Bettega]] || || {{suboff|72}}\n|-\n|CF || '''21''' || [[Paolo Rossi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF || '''4''' || [[Antonello Cuccureddu]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|FW || '''19''' || [[Francesco Graziani]] || || {{subon|72}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Friedl Koncilia]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Robert Sara]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Erich Obermayer]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Bruno Pezzey]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''14''' || [[Heinrich Strasser]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Josef Hickersberger]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' || [[Herbert Prohaska]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''12''' || [[Eduard Krieger]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Hans Krankl]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10''' || [[Wilhelm Kreuz]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''18''' || [[Walter Schachner]] || || {{suboff|63}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|FW ||'''19''' || [[Hans Pirkner]] || || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Senekowitsch]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Austria vs West Germany===\n{{main|Austria v West Germany (1978 FIFA World Cup)}}\n{{football box\n|date = 21 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|AUT}}\n|score = 3\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2217\n|team2 = {{fb|FRG}}\n|goals1 = [[Berti Vogts|Vogts]] {{goal|59|o.g.}}<br />[[Hans Krankl|Krankl]] {{goal|66||87}}\n|goals2 = [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge|Rummenigge]] {{goal|19}}<br />[[Bernd H\u00f6lzenbein|H\u00f6lzenbein]] {{goal|72}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Chateau Carreras|Estadio Chateau Carreras]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance = 38,318\n|referee = [[Abraham Klein (referee)|Abraham Klein]] ([[Israel Football Association|Israel]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Friedl Koncilia]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Robert Sara]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|85}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Erich Obermayer]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Bruno Pezzey]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''14''' || [[Heinrich Strasser]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Josef Hickersberger]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' || [[Herbert Prohaska]] || {{yel|69}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''12''' || [[Eduard Krieger]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Hans Krankl]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10''' || [[Wilhelm Kreuz]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''18''' || [[Walter Schachner]] || || {{suboff|71}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|FW ||'''17''' || [[Franz Oberacher]] || || {{subon|71}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Senekowitsch]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Sepp Maier]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Berti Vogts]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Bernard Dietz]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' || [[Rolf R\u00fcssmann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Manfred Kaltz]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Rainer Bonhof]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15''' || [[Erich Beer]] || || {{suboff|45}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''17'''|| [[Bernd H\u00f6lzenbein]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' || [[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik]] || {{yel|69}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''14''' || [[Dieter M\u00fcller]] || || {{suboff|60}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitute:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''20''' || [[Hansi M\u00fcller]] || || {{subon|45}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' || [[Klaus Fischer]] || || {{subon|60}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Helmut Sch\u00f6n]]\n|}\n|}\n\n===Italy vs Netherlands===\nThis match was a semifinal in all but name with the winner being assured a place in the final, although the Netherlands could advance with a draw and a Germany draw or loss. Italy started the positive and scored when [[Ernie Brandts]] in an attempt to stop [[Roberto Bettega]] only succeeded in putting the ball into his own net. The goal would have consequences for the Netherlands as [[Piet Schrijvers]] was injured on the play and had to be stretchered off for [[Jan Jongbloed]]. Italy dominated the remainder of the first half. In a physical match [[Johnny Rep]] was cautioned for fouling [[Romeo Benetti]], who was latter to pick up a yellow card himself for fouling Rensenbrink, meaning the Italian defender would miss the match should Italy reach it. Early in the second half [[Arie Haan]] was cautioned for a challenge on [[Marco Tardelli]] who later also picked up a yellow card meaning he too would miss Italy's next match. Some felt that [[Antonio Cabrini]]'s challenge on Haan many felt warranted a red card, not just a yellow. Shortly after half time Brandts, who earlier scored an own goal blasted home a shot to equalizes. Than fourteen minutes from time Haan hit an audacious shot 30 yards out that went off Zoff's left post an into the net.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/Italy.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=6 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622075829/http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/~goldkeep/Holland78/Italy.htm |archive-date=22 June 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n{{football box\n|date = 21 June 1978\n|time = 13:45 [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ITA}}\n|score = 1\u20132\n|report = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/argentina1978/matches/match/2391\n|team2 = {{fb|NED}}\n|goals1 = [[Ernie Brandts|Brandts]] {{goal|19|o.g.}}\n|goals2 = [[Ernie Brandts|Brandts]] {{goal|49}}<br />[[Arie Haan|Haan]] {{goal|76}}\n|stadium = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]], Buenos Aires\n|attendance = 67,433\n|referee = [[Angel Franco Mart\u00ednez]] ([[Royal Spanish Football Federation|Spain]]) }}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Dino Zoff]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''3''' || [[Antonio Cabrini]] || {{yel|65}}\n|-\n|DF || '''4''' || [[Antonello Cuccureddu]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Claudio Gentile]]\n|-\n|DF || '''8''' || [[Gaetano Scirea]]\n|-\n|MF || '''10''' || [[Romeo Benetti]] || {{yel|40}} || {{suboff|77}}\n|-\n|MF || '''14''' || [[Marco Tardelli]] || {{yel|70}}\n|-\n|MF || '''15''' || [[Renato Zaccarelli]]\n|-\n|MF || '''16''' || [[Franco Causio]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|CF || '''18''' || [[Roberto Bettega]]\n|-\n|CF || '''21''' || [[Paolo Rossi]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF || '''17''' || [[Claudio Sala]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|FW || '''19''' || [[Francesco Graziani]] || || {{subon|72}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Enzo Bearzot]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK || '''1''' || [[Piet Schrijvers]] || || {{suboff|21}}\n|-\n|DF || '''2''' || [[Jan Poortvliet]]\n|-\n|DF || '''5''' || [[Ruud Krol]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF || '''6''' || [[Wim Jansen]]\n|-\n|DF || '''22''' || [[Ernie Brandts]]\n|-\n|MF || '''13''' || [[Johan Neeskens]]\n|-\n|MF || '''9''' || [[Arie Haan]] || {{yel|50}}\n|-\n|MF|| '''10''' || [[Ren\u00e9 van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|MF || '''11''' || [[Willy van de Kerkhof]]\n|-\n|FW || '''16''' || [[Johnny Rep]] || {{yel|35}} || {{suboff|65}}\n|-\n|FW || '''12''' || [[Rob Rensenbrink]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|GK|| '''8''' || [[Jan Jongbloed]] || || {{subon|21}}\n|-\n|DF|| '''4''' || [[Adrie van Kraay]] || || {{subon|65}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|- \n|colspan=4|{{Flagicon|AUT}} [[Ernst Happel]]\n|}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1978 FIFA World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World}}\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup|Groups]]\n[[Category:West Germany at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|G]]\n[[Category:Italy at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|Group]]\n[[Category:Austria at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|Group]]\n[[Category:Netherlands at the 1978 FIFA World Cup|Group]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eItaly vs Netherlands:Typo fixing, replaced: latter \u2192 later", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1978_FIFA_World_Cup_Group_A"}
{"title_page": "People's Dispensary for Sick Animals", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name              = People's Dispensary for Sick Animals\n| logo              = PDSA_RGB_22-100mm.png\n| logo_size         = 200px\n| type              =\n| founded_date      = {{start date and age|1917}}\n| founder           = [[Maria Dickin]] CBE\n| location          = \n| origins           =\n| key_people        = \n| area_served       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| product           =\n| focus             = Animal welfare\n| method            =\n| revenue           = \n| endowment         =\n| num_volunteers    =\n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       =\n| owner             =\n| Non-profit_slogan =\n| homepage          = {{URL|http://pdsa.org.uk}}\n| dissolved         =\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n\nThe '''People's Dispensary for Sick Animals''' ('''PDSA''') is a [[veterinary]] [[Charitable organization|charity]] in the United Kingdom.  It was founded in 1917 by [[Maria Dickin]] to provide care for sick and injured animals of the poor. It is the UK's leading veterinary charity, carrying out more than one million free veterinary consultations a year, and  was up to 2009 the largest private employer of fully qualified [[veterinary surgeon]]s and [[Paraveterinary workers|veterinary nurse]]s in the UK, only those living within the PDSA's catchment areas can use their services.\n\n== Foundation and development ==\n\nDuring [[World War I]], animal welfare pioneer Maria Dickin worked to improve the dreadful state of animal health in the [[Whitechapel]] area of [[London]]. She wanted to open a clinic where [[East End]]ers living in poverty could receive free treatment for their sick and injured animals.   Despite widespread scepticism, she opened her free \"dispensary\" in a Whitechapel basement on Saturday 17 November 1917. It was an immediate success and she was soon forced to find larger premises.\n\nWithin six years, Maria Dickin had designed and equipped her first horse-drawn clinic, and soon a fleet of mobile dispensaries was established. PDSA vehicles soon became a common sight throughout the country. Eventually, PDSA's role was defined by two [[Acts of Parliament]], in 1949 and 1956, that continue to govern its activities today.\n\n== PDSA Dickin Medal ==\n\n[[Maria Dickin]] instituted the [[Dickin Medal]] in 1943 to acknowledge outstanding acts of bravery by animals serving with the Armed Forces or Civil Defence units.  It has become recognised as the animals' [[Victoria Cross]], and is administered by PDSA.  The PDSA created a second animal bravery award, the [[PDSA Gold Medal]], in 2002, which is now recognised as the animal equivalent of the [[George Cross]].\n\n== Eligibility requirements ==\n\nToday, treatment is only available to the pets of those in receipt of [[Housing Benefit]] or [[Council Tax#Council Tax Benefit|Council Tax Benefit]] and who live in one of the charity's 'catchment areas'.  For those eligible, treatment for sick and injured animals is free of charge. Recently, the PDSA started providing eligible pet owners with preventive services such as [[neutering]], [[vaccinations]] and [[Microchip implant (animal)|microchipping]].  These services are the only treatments that are '''not''' free; however, they are offered at cost price.\n\nAlthough there is no cost for all treatments except for those of a preventive nature, PDSA asks clients to make a donation of whatever they can afford towards the treatment of their animal.\n\nCurrently, PDSA is able to offer its services to 75% of eligible people, and has plans to increase this to 80% over the coming year.<ref name=Stat1>{{cite web | url=http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/registeredcharities/ScannedAccounts%5CEnds17%5C0000208217_ac_20051231_e_c.pdf |format=PDF| title = Annual Report, 2005 | publisher= PDSA | accessdate=2007-04-04}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009 the PDSA began requesting a donation on checking the animal in for treatment.\n\n== Areas of operation ==\n\n[[File:Mothers, Erdington, Birmingham, England - 2019-04-27 - Andy Mabbett - 17 (cropped).jpg|thumb| A PDSA [[charity shop]] in Birmingham, England, seen in April 2019]]\n\nPDSA operates throughout [[Great Britain]] through animal hospitals and practices; a vast network of [[charity shop]]s support the organisation.  It has one animal hospital in [[Northern Ireland]], the catchment area of which covers much of the area East of the [[River Bann|Bann]].  Although further hospitals are not currently planned for that region, some services through private clinics may be offered, and a charity shop is due to open in March 2007 in [[Lisburn]].  The charity's Head Office is based in [[Telford]], [[Shropshire]].\n\nIn 1937, a branch of the PDSA was founded in [[District Six]], [[South Africa]], which at the time was a poverty-stricken area of [[Cape Town]]. In 1988, the organization became autonomous but maintains a strong link with the mother society in the United Kingdom and a great deal of information is exchanged between them.<ref>[http://www.pdsa.org.za PDSA South Africa]</ref>\n\nIn October 1938 the PDSA held a Twenty-First Birthday Dinner at the Holborn Restaurant in London, attended by Mrs Dickin. There were words from abroad from [[France]] (Mr Horne), [[Dutch East Indies]] (Mr Cronin), [[Romania]] (Mr Smith), and [[Greece]] (Mr Hurle).\n\n== Celebrity Ambassadors ==\n*[[Joanna Page]]\n\n== Roobarb and Custard Partnership ==\n\nIn 2012 Bulldog Licensing, the brand licensing agency for [[Roobarb]] & Custard, pledged a [http://www.pdsa.org.uk/how-you-can-help/roobarb-custard/ long-term link with PDSA] to help raise \u00a31m. The characters have already appeared on a range of PDSA T-shirts, modelled and supported by singer and TV presenter [[Alesha Dixon]].\n\n== Pet Fit Club ==\n\nIn 2005 the PDSA launched its Pet Fit Club competition, in order to help battle the problem of pet [[obesity]]. The annual contest sees a group of overweight dogs, cats and rabbits embark on a strict six-month diet and exercise programme, specially tailored by PDSA vets and nurses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.petfitclub.org.uk/ |title=Pet Fit Club |publisher=PDSA |accessdate=18 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113001100/https://www.petfitclub.org.uk/ |archivedate=13 January 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> At the end of the programme the best-performing pet will be crowned slimmer of the year. In 2015, small furry pets such as guinea pigs, hamsters, rats and mice were allowed to take part in the competition for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dial2donate.org/the-pdsas-pet-fit-club-kicks-off/ |title=The PDSA's Pet Fit Club kicks off! |publisher=Dial2Donate |accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pdsa.org.uk PDSA Web site]\n* [http://www.intelligentgiving.com/charity/208217 Intelligent Giving profile of PDSA]\n* {{cite news <!-- Website is currently down - please add direct link to broadcast -->\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | title = Maria Dickin: founder of the PDSA\n  | work = [[Woman's Hour]]\n  | publisher = [[BBC Radio 4]]\n  | date = 24 December 2007\n  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/04/2007_52_mon.shtml?rss\n}}\n\n[[Category:Animal charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1917]]\n[[Category:Telford and Wrekin]]\n[[Category:Veterinary medicine in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name              = People's Dispensary for Sick Animals\n| logo              = PDSA_RGB_22-100mm.png\n| logo_size         = 200px\n| type              =\n| founded_date      = {{{start date and age|1917}}\n| founder           = [[Maria Dickin]] CBE\n| location          = \n| origins           =\n| key_people        = \n| area_served       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| product           =\n| focus             = Animal welfare\n| method            =\n| revenue           = \n| endowment         =\n| num_volunteers    =\n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       =\n| owner             =\n| Non-profit_slogan =\n| homepage          = {{URL|http://pdsa.org.uk}}\n| dissolved         =\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n\nThe '''People's Dispensary for Sick Animals''' ('''PDSA''') is a [[veterinary]] [[Charitable organization|charity]] in the United Kingdom.  It was founded in 1917 by [[Maria Dickin]] to provide care for sick and injured animals of the poor. It is the UK's leading veterinary charity, carrying out more than one million free veterinary consultations a year, and  was up to 2009 the largest private employer of fully qualified [[veterinary surgeon]]s and [[Paraveterinary workers|veterinary nurse]]s in the UK, only those living within the PDSA's catchment areas can use their services.\n\n== Foundation and development ==\n\nDuring [[World War I]], animal welfare pioneer Maria Dickin worked to improve the dreadful state of animal health in the [[Whitechapel]] area of [[London]]. She wanted to open a clinic where [[East End]]ers living in poverty could receive free treatment for their sick and injured animals.   Despite widespread scepticism, she opened her free \"dispensary\" in a Whitechapel basement on Saturday 17 November 1917. It was an immediate success and she was soon forced to find larger premises.\n\nWithin six years, Maria Dickin had designed and equipped her first horse-drawn clinic, and soon a fleet of mobile dispensaries was established. PDSA vehicles soon became a common sight throughout the country. Eventually, PDSA's role was defined by two [[Acts of Parliament]], in 1949 and 1956, that continue to govern its activities today.\n\n== PDSA Dickin Medal ==\n\n[[Maria Dickin]] instituted the [[Dickin Medal]] in 1943 to acknowledge outstanding acts of bravery by animals serving with the Armed Forces or Civil Defence units.  It has become recognised as the animals' [[Victoria Cross]], and is administered by PDSA.  The PDSA created a second animal bravery award, the [[PDSA Gold Medal]], in 2002, which is now recognised as the animal equivalent of the [[George Cross]].\n\n== Eligibility requirements ==\n\nToday, treatment is only available to the pets of those in receipt of [[Housing Benefit]] or [[Council Tax#Council Tax Benefit|Council Tax Benefit]] and who live in one of the charity's 'catchment areas'.  For those eligible, treatment for sick and injured animals is free of charge. Recently, the PDSA started providing eligible pet owners with preventive services such as [[neutering]], [[vaccinations]] and [[Microchip implant (animal)|microchipping]].  These services are the only treatments that are '''not''' free; however, they are offered at cost price.\n\nAlthough there is no cost for all treatments except for those of a preventive nature, PDSA asks clients to make a donation of whatever they can afford towards the treatment of their animal.\n\nCurrently, PDSA is able to offer its services to 75% of eligible people, and has plans to increase this to 80% over the coming year.<ref name=Stat1>{{cite web | url=http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/registeredcharities/ScannedAccounts%5CEnds17%5C0000208217_ac_20051231_e_c.pdf |format=PDF| title = Annual Report, 2005 | publisher= PDSA | accessdate=2007-04-04}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009 the PDSA began requesting a donation on checking the animal in for treatment.\n\n== Areas of operation ==\n\n[[File:Mothers, Erdington, Birmingham, England - 2019-04-27 - Andy Mabbett - 17 (cropped).jpg|thumb| A PDSA [[charity shop]] in Birmingham, England, seen in April 2019]]\n\nPDSA operates throughout [[Great Britain]] through animal hospitals and practices; a vast network of [[charity shop]]s support the organisation.  It has one animal hospital in [[Northern Ireland]], the catchment area of which covers much of the area East of the [[River Bann|Bann]].  Although further hospitals are not currently planned for that region, some services through private clinics may be offered, and a charity shop is due to open in March 2007 in [[Lisburn]].  The charity's Head Office is based in [[Telford]], [[Shropshire]].\n\nIn 1937, a branch of the PDSA was founded in [[District Six]], [[South Africa]], which at the time was a poverty-stricken area of [[Cape Town]]. In 1988, the organization became autonomous but maintains a strong link with the mother society in the United Kingdom and a great deal of information is exchanged between them.<ref>[http://www.pdsa.org.za PDSA South Africa]</ref>\n\nIn October 1938 the PDSA held a Twenty-First Birthday Dinner at the Holborn Restaurant in London, attended by Mrs Dickin. There were words from abroad from [[France]] (Mr Horne), [[Dutch East Indies]] (Mr Cronin), [[Romania]] (Mr Smith), and [[Greece]] (Mr Hurle).<ref>[Original Menu]</ref>\n\n== Celebrity Ambassadors ==\n*[[Joanna Page]]\n\n== Roobarb and Custard Partnership ==\n\nIn 2012 Bulldog Licensing, the brand licensing agency for [[Roobarb]] & Custard, pledged a [http://www.pdsa.org.uk/how-you-can-help/roobarb-custard/ long-term link with PDSA] to help raise \u00a31m. The characters have already appeared on a range of PDSA T-shirts, modelled and supported by singer and TV presenter [[Alesha Dixon]].\n\n== Pet Fit Club ==\n\nIn 2005 the PDSA launched its Pet Fit Club competition, in order to help battle the problem of pet [[obesity]]. The annual contest sees a group of overweight dogs, cats and rabbits embark on a strict six-month diet and exercise programme, specially tailored by PDSA vets and nurses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.petfitclub.org.uk/ |title=Pet Fit Club |publisher=PDSA |accessdate=18 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113001100/https://www.petfitclub.org.uk/ |archivedate=13 January 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> At the end of the programme the best-performing pet will be crowned slimmer of the year. In 2015, small furry pets such as guinea pigs, hamsters, rats and mice were allowed to take part in the competition for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dial2donate.org/the-pdsas-pet-fit-club-kicks-off/ |title=The PDSA's Pet Fit Club kicks off! |publisher=Dial2Donate |accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pdsa.org.uk PDSA Web site]\n* [http://www.intelligentgiving.com/charity/208217 Intelligent Giving profile of PDSA]\n* {{cite news <!-- Website is currently down - please add direct link to broadcast -->\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | title = Maria Dickin: founder of the PDSA\n  | work = [[Woman's Hour]]\n  | publisher = [[BBC Radio 4]]\n  | date = 24 December 2007\n  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/04/2007_52_mon.shtml?rss\n}}\n\n[[Category:Animal charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1917]]\n[[Category:Telford and Wrekin]]\n[[Category:Veterinary medicine in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Catlemur", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/People%27s_Dispensary_for_Sick_Animals"}
{"title_page": "Amit Shah", "text_new": "{{short description|Minister of Home Affairs (India)}}\n{{for|other people with the same name|Amit Shah (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2014}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| birth_name = Amit Anilchandra Shah\n| image = [[File:Amit shah official portrait.jpg|220px|border]]\n| image_size = 220px\n| Caption = \n| office = [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n| predecessor = [[Rajnath Singh]]\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start = 30 May 2019\n| office1 = [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|Chairperson of the National Democratic Alliance]]\n| predecessor1 = [[L. K. Advani]]\n| successor1 = \n| term_start1 = 9 July 2014\n| office2 = [[List of Presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President of the Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Rajnath Singh]]\n| successor2 = [[Jagat Prakash Nadda]]\n| term_start2 = 9 July 2014\n| term_end2 = 20 January 2020\n| office3 = [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|Member of Parliament]]<br>[[Lok Sabha]]\n| majority3 = 5,57,014 (43.38%)\n| term_start3 = 23 May 2019\n| predecessor3 = [[L. K. Advani]]\n| constituency3 = [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]]\n| office4 = [[Member of parliament, Rajya Sabha|Member of Parliament]]<br>[[Rajya Sabha]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Dilip Pandya]]\n| successor4 = [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]]\n| constituency4 = [[Gujarat]]\n| term_start4 = 19 August 2017\n| term_end4 = 29 May 2019\n| office5 = [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly|Member of the Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start5 = 2012\n| term_end5 = 2017\n| constituency5 = [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]]\n| predecessor5 = ''office established''\n| successor5 = [[Kaushik Patel (politician)|Kaushik Patel]]\n| term_start6 = 1997\n| term_end6 = 2012\n| successor6 = ''office abolished''\n| predecessor6 = [[Harishchandra Patel|Harishchandra Lavjibhai Patel]]\n| constituency6 = [[Sarkhej (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sarkhej]]\n| office7 = [[Minister of State]], [[Government of Gujarat]]\n| term_start7 = 2002\n| term_end7 = 2012\n| 1blankname7 = Departments\n| 1namedata7 = Home, Law and Justice, Prison, Border Security, Civil Defence, Excise, Home Guards, Transport, Prohibition, Gram Rakshak Dal, Police Housing, Legislative and Parliamentary Affairs\n| 2blankname7 = Chief Minister\n| 2namedata7 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|10|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"IE_2014_prepares\"/>\n| birth_place = [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| spouse = Sonal Shah\n| children = [[Jay Shah]]\n| alma_mater = [[Gujarat University]] ([[B.Sc.]])\n| website = {{URL|www.amitshah.co.in}}\n}}\n'''Amit Anilchandra Shah'''<ref name=\"Jagran\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jagranjosh.com/general-knowledge/amit-shah-biography-1558610444-1|title=Amit Shah Union Home Minister of India 2019 : Age, Family, Political Life and Interesting Facts|date=16 August 2019}}</ref> (born 22 October 1964) is an Indian politician serving as [[Minister of Home Affairs(India)|Minister of Home Affairs]] who has served as [[List of Presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) from 2014 to 2020. He was elected to the lower House of Parliament the [[Lok Sabha]] in the [[2019 Indian general election]] from [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]]. He was earlier elected  as a  member of the  upper House of Parliament the [[Rajya Sabha]] from [[Gujarat]] in 2017. He also became the youngest serving full-time [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Home Minister]] at an age of 54.<ref name=\"Jagran\"/> He is the chief strategist of the BJP and a close aide to [[Narendra Modi]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/amit-shah-bjps-chanakya-who-delivered-modi-wave-2-0/articleshow/69465902.cms | title=Amit Shah: BJP's 'Chanakya' who delivered Modi Wave 2.0 | publisher=[[The Times of India]] | date=23 May 2019 | accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/lok-sabha-2019/story/amit-shah-bjp-s-chanakya-strategised-modi-wave-2-0-1532943-2019-05-23 | title=Amit Shah: BJP's Chanakya who strategised and delivered Modi wave 2.0 | publisher=India Today | date=23 May 2019 | accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his college days Shah was a member of [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad|ABVP]], student wing of the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|RSS]]. At the age of 18, he secured a position in the ABVP, and joined the BJP in 1987. Shah was first elected in Gujarat as the [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] for a seat partly covering [[Ahmedabad]], [[Sarkhej (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sarkhej]] in 1997 (a by-election) holding it in 1998, 2002 and 2007 until the seat's 2008 dissolution, then for nearby [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]], from [[2012 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2012]]-2017. He is a close associate of Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and held executive portfolios in the [[Government of Gujarat|state government]] during Modi's tenure as its Chief Minister.\n\nShah was the BJP's in-charge for India's largest and politically most crucial state, [[Uttar Pradesh]], during the [[2014 Lok Sabha elections]]. The BJP and its allies swept the state, registering their best performance, by winning 73 out of 80 seats. As a result, Shah rose to national prominence and was appointed as the party's national president in July 2014.<ref name=\"IT_new_2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/20140728-rahul-kanwal-on-the-man-behind-the-reputation-amit-shah-bjp-804608-2014-07-17 |title=Inside the mind of Amit Shah: All eyes on new BJP chief as party gears up for battle in five states |date=17 July 2014 |publisher=India Today }}</ref>\n\nHe has played an organising and membership-promotional role in elections of many states since 2014. In his initial two years, the BJP achieved success in Legislative Assembly elections in [[2014 Maharashtra Legislative Assembly election|Maharashtra]], [[2014 Haryana Legislative Assembly election|Haryana]], [[2014 Jammu and Kashmir Legislative Assembly election|Jammu & Kashmir]], [[2014 Jharkhand Legislative Assembly election|Jharkhand]] in 2014 and in [[Assam]] but lost ground in [[2015 Delhi Legislative Assembly election|Delhi]] and the large eastern state of [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|Bihar]] in 2015.\n\nHe was in 2017 partly credited with the party landslides in [[2017 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|Uttar Pradesh]], [[2017 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|Uttarakhand]] and the party's modern heartland state of [[2017 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/elections/gujarat-2017/live-updates-2017-gujarat-legislative-assembly-election-results/article21830220.ece|title=Gujarat Assembly election results: Counting ends as BJP closes out Gujarat with 99 seats; Congress claims 77|last=Desk|first=The Hindu Net|date=18 December 2017|work=The Hindu|access-date=27 August 2018|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> in which year was marked the party's strong debut in much smaller [[2017 Manipur Legislative Assembly election|Manipur]], but the [[Shiromani Akali Dal|Akali]]-BJP alliance lost power in considerably larger [[2017 Punjab Legislative Assembly election|Punjab]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/punjab-election-result-2017-triangular-battle-between-akali-dal-bjp-congress-aap-1668526|title=Punjab Election Result 2017: Congress' Amarinder Singh Defeats Akali Dal-BJP, AAP - Highlights|work=NDTV.com|access-date=27 August 2018}}</ref> In 2018 the party lost power in the states of [[2018 Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly election|Chhattisgarh]], [[2018 Rajasthan Legislative Assembly election|Rajasthan]] and [[2018 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|Madhya Pradesh]]. The next year, BJP won 303 seats to get majority in the [[2019 Indian general election]], making Shah the most successful BJP President ever.<ref name=\"ET_most_successful\">{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/amit-shah-in-new-role-after-being-most-successful-bjp-chief/articleshow/69584774.cms |title=Amit Shah in new role after being most successful BJP chief |date=30 May 2019 |newspaper=Economic Times }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nShah was born in [[Mumbai]] on 22 October 1964.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/politics/amit-shah-an-organisation-man-at-helm-114071000099_1.html |title=Amit Shah: An organisation man at helm |author=Premal Balan |date=10 July 2014 |newspaper=Business Standard }}</ref> He came from a [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] [[Hindu]] [[Vaishnava]] family who were [[Baniya]]s.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/i-am-a-hindu-vaishnav-not-jain-amit-shah-1833945|title=\"I Am A Hindu Vaishnav, Not Jain\": Amit Shah|website=NDTV.com|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|quote=Amit Shah, himself a baniya |url=https://www.newsclick.in/amit-shah-borrowed-phrase-jinnah-when-he-dubbed-gandhi-chatur-bania|first=Shamsul|last=Islam|date=14 June 2017|publisher=Newsclick|title=Amit Shah Borrowed a Phrase from Jinnah when he Dubbed Gandhi a 'Chatur Bania'}}</ref> His great grandfather was the Nagarseth of the small [[Mansa, Gujarat#History|state of Mansa]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/amit-shah-the-strategist-of-bjp-s-india-game-plan/story-Fr0sSiYHtTwhVxKBsjapsI.html|title=The 'Shah' of BJP's game plan who wants to alter India's political culture|date=16 July 2016|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> His father Anil Chandra Shah, a businessman from [[Mansa, Gujarat|Mansa]], owned a successful [[polyvinyl chloride|PVC]] [[plastic pipework|pipe]] business.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He did his schooling in [[Mehsana]] and moved to [[Ahmedabad]] to study [[biochemistry]] at CU Shah Science College. He graduated with a [[B.Sc.]] degree in biochemistry, and then worked for his father's business.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He also worked as a stockbroker and in co-operative banks in Ahmedabad.<ref name=\"rediff_2010_fall\">{{cite news |url=http://news.rediff.com/special/2010/jul/24/what-amit-shahs-fall-really-means.htm |title=What Amit Shah's fall really means |author=Sheela Bhatt |website=rediff.com |date=28 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nShah was involved with the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] since childhood, participating in the neighbourhood ''shakhas'' (branches) as a boy. He formally became an RSS ''swayamsevak'' (volunteer) during his college days in Ahmedabad.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> He first met Narendra Modi in 1982 through Ahmedabad RSS circles.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\">{{cite news |url=http://www.openthemagazine.com/article/india/his-master-s-mind |title=His Master's Mind |publisher=Open |author=PR Ramesh |date=11 April 2014 }}</ref> At that time, Modi was an RSS ''pracharak'' (propagator), working as in-charge of youth activities in city.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\n== Early political career ==\nShah started his political career as a leader of the student wing of the RSS, the [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad]], in 1983.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/><ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\">{{cite news |title = Who is Amit Shah? |url=https://www.ndtv.com/people/who-is-amit-shah-525154 |publisher=NDTV |date=12 June 2013}}</ref> He joined BJP in 1987, one year before Modi joined the party.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He became an activist of BJP's youth wing [[Bharatiya Janata Yuva Morcha]] (BJYM) in 1987. He then gradually rose in the BJYM hierarchy, holding various posts including that of ward secretary, [[taluka]] secretary, state secretary, vice-president, and general secretary.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> He came into limelight for his excellent management when he was the election campaign manager for [[Lal Krishna Advani]] in Gandhinagar during the [[1991 Indian general election|1991 Lok Sabha elections]].<ref name=\"IE_2014_prepares\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bjp-union-home-ministry-amit-shah-1539468-2019-05-31 | title=From sticking bills for BJP to managing Union home ministry: Rise and rise of Amit Shah | publisher=India Today | work=Prabhash K Dutta | date=31 May 2019 | accessdate=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, BJP formed its first government in Gujarat, with [[Keshubhai Patel]] as the Chief Minister. At that time, BJP's main rival [[Indian National Congress]] was highly influential in rural Gujarat. Modi and Shah worked together to decimate Congress in the rural areas. Their strategy was to find the second most influential leader in every village, and get him or her to join BJP. They created a network of 8,000 influential rural leaders who had lost elections to the ''pradhan'' (village chief) post in various villages.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/>\n\nModi and Shah used the same strategy to reduce Congress' influence over the state's powerful [[co-operative]]s, which play an important role in the state's economy. In 1999, Shah was elected as the president of Ahmedabad District Cooperative Bank (ADCB), the biggest cooperative bank in India. In Gujarat, such elections had traditionally been won on the [[Indian caste system|caste]] considerations, and the co-operative banks had traditionally been controlled by [[Patel]]s, [[Gaderia]]s and [[Kshatriya]]s. Despite not belonging to any of these castes, Shah won the election. At that time, the bank was on the verge of collapsing, having accumulated losses of {{INR}} 36 [[crore]]. Shah turned around the bank's fortune within a year's time: the next year, the bank registered a profit of {{INR}} 27 crore. By 2014, the bank's profit had increased to around {{INR}} 250 crore.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Shah also ensured that 11 of the Bank's 22 directors were BJP loyalists.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nModi and Shah also sought to reduce the Congress hold over sports bodies in the state.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Shah served as the president of Gujarat State Chess Association.<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/> In 2009, he became the vice-president of the cash-rich [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] (GCA), when Narendra Modi served as its president.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> In 2014, after Modi became [[Prime Minister of India]], Shah became the president of GCA.\n\nModi, who had become a general secretary in the party's state unit by the early 1990s, used his influence to get bigger roles for Shah. He convinced Patel to appoint Shah as the chairman of the [[Gujarat State Financial Corporation]], a public sector financial institution which finances small and medium-scale enterprises. After [[Shankersinh Vaghela]] and some other leaders complained about Modi's growing clout in the Gujarat government, the party leadership moved Modi out of Gujarat, to the BJP headquarters in Delhi. During this time (1995-2001), Shah served as Modi's informer in Gujarat.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nIn 1997, Modi lobbied to get Shah a BJP ticket for the [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]] by-election in [[Sarkhej]].<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\">{{cite news |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/The-importance-of-Amit-Shah/articleshow/33378596.cms |title=The importance of Amit Shah |newspaper=Mumbai Mirror |date=7 April 2014 }}</ref> Shah became an MLA in February 1997 after winning the by-election.<ref name=\"Andy2014\">{{cite book |author=Andy Marino |title=Narendra Modi: A Political Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ylIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT76 |date=8 April 2014 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |isbn=978-93-5136-218-0 |pages=76\u2013}}</ref> He retained his seat in the 1998 Assembly elections.<ref name=\"rediff_1998_Sarkhej\"/>\n\n== Gujarat's minister==\n[[File:PM Modii addresses a BJP National Council Meet.jpg|thumb|PM Modi addresses a BJP National Council Meet]]\nIn October 2001, BJP replaced Keshubhai Patel with Narendra Modi as the chief minister of Gujarat, following allegations of inefficient administration. Over the next few years, Modi and Shah gradually sidelined their political rivals.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nShah contested the [[2002 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2002 Assembly election]] from the [[Sarkhej]] constituency in Ahmedabad. He won by the highest margin among all candidates: 158,036 votes. In the [[2007 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2007 Assembly election]], he won from Sarkhej again, improving his margin of victory.<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/>\n\nDuring Narendra Modi's twelve-year tenure as the Gujarat CM, Shah emerged as one of the most powerful leaders in Gujarat. After winning the 2002 elections, he became the youngest minister in the Modi government, and was given multiple portfolios.<ref name=\"IE_2014_prepares\">{{cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/2013/jul/07/In-UP-Shah-prepares-for-Modi-ahead-of-2014-battle-494331.html |title=In UP, Shah prepares for Modi ahead of 2014 battle |date=7 July 2013 |newspaper=Indian Express |author=Subhash Mishra and Pratul Sharma}}</ref> At one time, he held 12 portfolios: Home, Law and Justice, Prison, Border Security, Civil Defence, Excise, Transport, Prohibition, Home Guards, Gram Rakshak Dal, Police Housing, and Legislative and Parliamentary Affairs.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\">{{cite news |url=https://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/organiser |title=The Organiser |author=Poornima Joshi |publisher=Caravan |date=1 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the Congress-led Central Government announced its intention to repeal the [[Prevention of Terrorism Act, 2002|Prevention of Terrorism Act]], calling it regressive. Shah piloted the [[Gujarat Control of Organised Crime Act|Gujarat Control of Organised Crime]] (Amendment) Bill through Gujarat state assembly amid an opposition walk-out.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/gujarat-keeps-a-terror-law-spare/cid/737976 | location=Calcutta, India | work=The Telegraph | title=Gujarat keeps a terror law spare | date=3 June 2004}}</ref>\n\nShah also played an important role in convincing the Narendra Modi government to pass the [[Gujarat Freedom of Religion Bill|Gujarat Freedom of Religion Act]], which made religious conversions difficult in Hindu-majority Gujarat. His opponents argued that the Act went against the rights guaranteed by the [[Indian Constitution]], but Shah defended the bill, calling it a measure against forced conversions. His efforts in getting the bill passed impressed the senior leadership of RSS.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\" />\n\n==Politics==\n\n=== Police encounter cases ===\n[[File:Amit Shah and Udit Raj.jpg|thumb|Amit Shah and Udit Raj]]\nIn 2010, Shah was accused of having orchestrated the extrajudicial killings of criminal <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/who-was-sohrabuddin-sheikh-424777|title = Who was Sohrabuddin Sheikh| publisher=NDTV.com | date = 27 July 2010 }}</ref> [[Sohrabuddin Sheikh]], his wife Kauser Bi and his criminal associate [[Tulsiram Prajapati]]. According to the [[Central Bureau of Investigation|CBI]], Sohrabuddin had been harassing some [[marble]] traders of Rajasthan, by demanding hefty [[protection racket|protection]] money. CBI claimed that two of these marble traders paid Shah to eliminate Sohrabuddin. He, along with the police officers [[Deputy inspector general of police|DIG]] [[D. G. Vanzara|DG Vanzara]] and [[Superintendent of police (India)|SP]] Rajkumar Pandian, allegedly hatched a plan to kill Sohrabuddin. In 2004, [[List of police ranks in India|DCP]] Abhay Chudasama pressured Sohrabuddin and Tulsiram to fire at the office of two builder brothers - Raman Patel and Dashrath Patel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-sohrabuddin-case-how-patel-bros-were-fleeced-1420791 |author=Nikunj Soni |title=Sohrabuddin case: How Patel bros were 'fleeced' |date=9 August 2010 |newspaper=DNA }}</ref> This was done so that a fresh criminal case could be registered against Sohrabuddin and Tulsiram. The next year, the police picked up Sohrabuddin, Kausar Bi and Tulsiram, and took them to a farmhouse near Ahmedabad. Sohrabuddin was killed in a staged attack, with Vanzara claiming that he was a [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] operative. Kausar Bi was also killed and cremated for being a witness. Tulsiram was initially let off, as he was an informer of Vanzara. He was eliminated later, after Sohrabuddin's death was exposed as an extrajudicial killing by a journalist. CBI claimed that Shah had transferred Vanzara to various places in order to facilitate these killings.<ref name=\"rediff_2007_cracked\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/apr/25spec.htm |title=The journalist who cracked Gujarat fake encounter case |date=25 April 2007 |website=rediff.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/cop-transfers-part-of-shah-plan/story-cFpY9WJFOTx9Los8qmjbGL.html |title=Cop transfers part of Shah plan |publisher=Hindustan Times |author=Abhishek Sharan |date=26 July 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018155653/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/Cop-transfers-part-of-Shah-plan/Article1-577692.aspx |archivedate=18 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nVanzara and several other officers were arrested in the case. As proof of Shah's involvement in the crimes, the CBI presented phone call records, which showed that Shah had been in touch with the accused police officers when the victims were in their illegal custody. It also presented videotapes of Patel brothers' conversations with two of Shah's associates at Ahmedabad District Cooperative Bank (ADCB). In the tape, ADCB Director Yashpal Chudasama and its Chairman [[Ajay Patel]] can be seen asking the brothers not to involve Shah's name in the case. Yashpal Chudasama is the brother of the accused police officer Abhay Chudasama. According to CBI, Abhay used to run an extortion racket, with Sohrabuddin as his henchman.<ref name=\"IBNLive_2010_proof\">{{cite news |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/cbi-proof-against-shah-sohrabuddin-tapes/127540-37.html |title=CBI 'proof' against Shah: Sohrabuddin tapes |date=26 July 2010 |author=Bhupendra Chaubey |publisher=CNN-IBN }}</ref> The Patel brothers, who had several criminal cases against them, also spoke against Shah. They claimed that the police had falsely implicated them into various cases between 2001\u20132005 in order to extort money from them. They also claimed that Vanzara made them talk to Shah over phone, and Shah threatened them into giving a statement against Sohrabuddin and Tulsiram. They further stated that, in 2006, [[Ajay Patel]] and Abhay Chudasama called them again on behalf of Shah, asking them to give certain statements to CBI.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/he-(amit-shah)-smiled-and-said-sohrabuddin-had-himself-closed-the-option-of-keeping-himself-alive.../658769/0 |title=He (Amit Shah) smiled and said Sohrabuddin had himself closed the option of keeping himself alive... |date=24 November 2011 |newspaper=Indian Express }}</ref>\n\nShah dismissed all the accusations against him as politically motivated. He pointed out that during his tenure as the Home Minister, Gujarat was one of the states with minimum number of police encounters in the country. He stated that he kept in touch with the police officers on the phone in the normal course of his duties as the home minister.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-11-14/news/44075365_1_sadiq-jamal-ishrat-jahan-amit-shah |title=CBI to file crucial charge-sheets in Gujarat fake encounters' case |author=Aman Sharma |newspaper=Economic times |date=14 November 2013 }}</ref> He accused the Congress of misusing CBI, and claimed that only the encounter cases in Gujarat were being scrutinised when the rest of the country had witnessed around 1500 encounters during the same period.<ref name=\"rediff_2013_waiting\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-exclusive-amit-shah-interview-people-are-waiting-to-vote-for-modi/20131008.htm#3 |title=Encounter cases are politically motivated; non-Gujarat encounters are never scrutinised |date=8 October 2013 |author=Sheela Bhatt |website=rediff.com }}</ref> He said that if CBI had any solid evidence against him, it would have been able to frame charges against him.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> In 2010, Police Commissioner Geeta Johri, who first investigated the case, claimed that CBI was pressurizing her to falsely implicate Shah in the Sohrabuddin case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/cbi-putting-pressure-on-me-geeta-johri/article599990.ece |title=CBI putting pressure on me: Geeta Johri |author=J. Venkatesan |newspaper=The Hindu |date=29 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nDG Vanzara was also accused in the [[Ishrat Jahan]] fake encounter case, but the CBI gave Shah a clean sheet in the case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/CBI-clean-chit-for-Amit-Shah-in-Ishrat-Jahan-encounter-case/articleshow/34784569.cms |title=CBI clean chit for Amit Shah in Ishrat Jahan encounter case |date=7 May 2014 |newspaper=The Times of India }}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest and exile ===\nShah was arrested on 25 July 2010 in connection with the [[Death of Sohrabuddin Sheikh|Sohrabuddin case]]. He was [[Indian Penal Code|charged]] with the murder, extortion, and kidnapping among other charges. At one time, Shah was considered as one of the main contenders for the Gujarat Chief Minister's post. However, his political career was hurt by the arrest. Many leaders in the Gujarat government distanced themselves from him. His fellow ministers considered him as an autocratic person, who did not have good relations with his colleagues.<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/>\n\nWhen Shah applied for bail, the CBI raised concerns that he would use his political power to prevent justice from taking its course.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> The [[Gujarat High Court]] granted him bail three months after his arrest, on Friday, 29 October 2010. However, the next day, when the courts were closed, Justice [[Aftab Alam (judge)|Aftab Alam]] took a petition at his residence to bar him from entering Gujarat.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Shah was thus forcibly exiled from the state from 2010 to 2012.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He and his wife moved to a room in Gujarat Bhavan, Delhi.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Later, the Supreme Court canceled his bail on a CBI plea. In September 2012, the Supreme Court granted him bail, and allowed him to return to Gujarat. He then contested and won the [[2012 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2012 Assembly election]] from [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]] constituency (the Sarkhej constituency had ceased to exist after delimitation).<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/>\n\n=\n\n== Rise in national politics ==\nAfter Narendra Modi became the Prime Ministerial candidate of BJP, Shah's influence also increased in the party. The two have been accused of sidelining other BJP leaders such as [[Lal Krishna Advani]], [[Sushma Swaraj]], [[Murli Manohar Joshi]] and [[Jaswant Singh]].<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> By this time, Shah had gained recognition as an excellent election campaign manager, and had been dubbed a \"modern-day [[Chanakya]] and master strategist\".<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/amit-shah-set-for-bigger-role-if-bjp-wins/article5903327.ece Amit Shah set for bigger role if BJP wins], Vinay Kumar, 12 April 2014</ref> Shah was appointed as a BJP general secretary, and was given charge of [[Uttar Pradesh]] (UP). He was chosen not by Modi, but by Rajnath Singh, who had been impressed by the skills that Shah displayed in wresting control of various Congress-controlled organizations in Gujarat.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> The decision did not go down well with many in the party, who saw him as a liability owing to the criminal charges against him. Political analysts such as [[Shekhar Gupta]] termed the decision as a blunder.<ref name=\"Shekhar2014\">{{cite book |author=Shekhar Gupta |title=Anticipating India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TipIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT369 |date=8 April 2014 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |isbn=978-93-5136-256-2 |page=369 }}</ref>\n\n=== Uttar Pradesh general elections ===\nShah's political career, which had declined after his arrest in 2010, revived after BJP's victory in the [[2014 Indian general election|2014 general election]]. In UP, where Shah was the in-charge, BJP and its allies won 73 out of 80 seats. Shah had been made in charge of BJP's UP campaigning on 12 June 2013, less than a year before the elections.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Since February 2012, Shah had spent considerable time in UP, trying to understand the reasons for the [[Samajwadi Party]]'s winning performance in the [[2012 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|2012 UP Assembly elections]]. Shah realised that the voters were dissatisfied with the Samajwadi Party, which he believed had failed to keep its election promises after the win. He also took advantage of the [[Other Backward Classes|OBC]] voters' displeasure with the UP government's decision to create 4.5% [[reservation in India|reservation]] for the minorities within the 27% OBC quota in government jobs and education.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nShah personally oversaw the candidate selection, emphasizing on the candidate's local clout and winning potential as the only criteria for selection, as opposed to the candidate's party loyalty or ideology. His team estimated that only 35% of the BJP's traditional supporters had actually voted in the UP elections. Therefore, he focused on door-to-door campaigning at the [[voting booth|booth]]-level. He set up a 7-to-10 member management committee for each of the 140,000 voting booths in the state. For each booth, his team collated lists of voters and reached out to them.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Shah's team used 450 GPS-enabled mobile vans (\"video [[Ratha|raths]]\") to reach out to the masses in remote areas, where media reach was negligible.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140518/commentary-op-ed/article/sunday-interview-amit-shah |title=Sunday Interview: We had 450 video raths with GPS and I'd get feedback on my mobile, says Amit Shah |newspaper=Deccan Chronicle | date=18 May 2014 |author=Yojna Gosai }}</ref> Shah personally covered 76 out of 80 Lok Sabha constituencies. He also insisted on Modi contesting election from [[Varanasi]].<ref name=\"Outlook_2014_Feast\">{{cite news |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Judgement-Day-Feast-For-The-Shah-Of-Shahs/290749 |title=Judgement Day Feast For The Shah Of Shahs |author=Prarthna Gahilote |publisher=Outlook |date=26 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nShah convinced Modi to utilize RSS volunteers for grassroots campaigning, which proved highly beneficial for BJP.<ref name=\"Outlook_2014_Feast\"/> Although RSS officially did not get involved in electioneering, Shah used its volunteers to mobilize and monitor the campaigners. For example, the RSS volunteers would cross-check a BJP worker's claims of having targeted a given number of households.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Shah also helped organize \"mega rallies\" for Modi. Like other major political parties, BJP provisioned one van per village to transport people to the rally venue. However, unlike others, Shah decided that BJP would not provide money for hiring these vehicles. Instead, he declared that the party workers organizing the transportation would be made the leaders of the BJP units in their respective villages. This strategy ensured that a number of local village leaders developed a stake in Modi's victory.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/>\n\nCritics accused Shah of trying to polarize the UP voters along the religious lines. While visiting [[Ayodhya]] for a meeting with the party's local committee, he raised the [[Ram Janmabhoomi]] temple issue (see [[Ayodhya dispute]]). BJP fielded three candidates accused of inciting violence during the [[2013 Muzaffarnagar riots]]. These were seen as attempts to target the party's [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] base.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> An [[First Information Report|FIR]] was registered against Shah for a speech in Muzaffarnagar, where he urged the voters to seek \"revenge\" through their votes.<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\"/> He also took advantage of Shia Muslim antipathy towards Sunni Muslims in [[Lucknow]].<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21627719-narendra-modi-relies-most-two-men-who-could-hardly-be-less-alike-enablers The enablers: Narendra Modi relies most on two men who could hardly be less alike], economist.com.</ref>\n\nShah also played an important role in BJP's election campaigning strategy outside Uttar Pradesh. He focused on building Modi's image as a strong leader. At times, he opposed even Modi on several strategic campaigning issues. For example, when Modi praised his opponent and prospective post-poll ally [[Mamata Banerjee]], Shah insisted that BJP must not divert from the \"Modi-versus-all\" tactic.<ref name=\"Outlook_2014_Feast\"/> Shah was also responsible for forging BJP's alliances with regional parties like [[Pattali Makkal Katchi]].<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\"/>\n\n== BJP President  ==\n[[File:Modi congratulates Amit Shah as he becomes BJP President.jpg|thumb|Modi congratulates Amit Shah as he becomes BJP President]]\nIn July 2014, BJP's Central Parliamentary Board unanimously approved Shah's appointment as president of the party.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-07-09/news/51247833_1_bjp-president-rajnath-singh-nitin-gadkari |title=BJP strategist & Narendra Modi's confidant Amit Shah appointed party president |date=9 July 2014 |newspaper=Economic Times}}</ref> He was reelected BJP President unanimously on 24 January 2016.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/amit-shah-reelected-bjp-president/article8147827.ece Amit Shah re-elected BJP president]. The Hindu, 25 January 2016.</ref>\n\nAfter becoming party president, Shah started an aggressive membership drive and by March 2015 BJP claimed 100 million members.<ref>{{citation |title=BJP becomes largest political party in the world |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/BJP-becomes-largest-political-party-in-the-world/articleshow/46739025.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=30 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Move Over, CCP: India's BJP Now the World's Largest Political Party |url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/04/move-over-ccp-indias-bjp-now-the-worlds-largest-political-party |work=[[The Diplomat]] |date=9 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nUnder his leadership during 2014\u201316, BJP achieved success in Legislative Assembly elections in [[2014 Maharashtra Legislative Assembly election|Maharashtra]], [[2014 Haryana Legislative Assembly election|Haryana]], [[2014 Jammu and Kashmir Legislative Assembly election|Jammu & Kashmir]], [[2014 Jharkhand Legislative Assembly election|Jharkhand]]  and [[2016 Assam Legislative Assembly election|Assam]], but lost the elections in [[2015 Delhi Legislative Assembly election|Delhi]] and [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|Bihar]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/comment-bihar-elections-2015-has-amit-shah-lost-his-inner-chanakya-2143597 |title=Bihar Elections 2015: Has BJP President Amit Shah lost his inner Chanakya? |author=Arghya Roy |newspaper=DNA |date=9 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nShah also spearheaded campaigning in the 2017 assembly elections, which gave BJP resounding success in [[2017 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|Uttar Pradesh]] and [[2017 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|Uttarakhand]], meaning the party won its greatest run in percentage terms in recent state assembly elections: 325 seats out of 403.<ref>{{citation |title=Uttar Pradesh election results: How BJP chief Amit Shah crafted a winning strategy for PM Modi |url=http://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uttar-pradesh-election-results-how-bjp-chief-amit-shah-crafted-a-winning-strategy-for-pm-modi/articleshow/57589801.cms |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=11 March 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Narendra Modi's B.J.P. Party Wins Big in Uttar Pradesh, India's Largest State |url=https://mobile.nytimes.com/2017/03/11/world/asia/narendra-modis-party-wins-big-in-uttar-pradesh-indias-largest-state.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=11 March 2017 }}</ref> BJP made some headway into [[2017 Manipur Legislative Assembly election|Manipur]].<ref>{{citation |title=How Amit Shah won U.P., one booth at a time |url=http://www.thehindu.com/elections/uttar-pradesh-2017/how-amit-shah-won-up-one-booth-at-a-time/article17448474.ece |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=11 March 2017 |last1=Hebbar |first1=Nistula }}</ref> Under his stewardship, the BJP has also won 2017 Gujarat Legislative Assembly polls for a record six times and wrested power from the [[Indian National Congress|INC]] during the 2017 Himachal Pradesh Legislative Assembly polls. In March 2018, BJP won first time in the left-ruled northeastern state of Tripura with a two-thirds majority. BJP also made gains in Nagaland and Meghalaya and formed government in both states with its allies.\n\nIn 2018, Shah said millions of \"illegal infiltrators\" have entered the country like \"termites\" and should be \"uprooted\": \"Should they be thrown out or not? Millions of infiltrators have entered our country and are eating the country like termites. Should we not uproot them?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/09/bjp-chief-slammed-calling-bangladesh-migrants-termites-180924155313048.html|date=24 September 2018|title=BJP chief slammed for calling Bangladeshi migrants 'termites'|work=Al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\nShah led BJP to victory in the [[2019 Indian general election]], becoming the most successful BJP President ever, in the process.<ref name=\"ET_most_successful\"/> During the election campaign, he visited 312 of the 543 [[List of constituencies of the Lok Sabha|Lok Sabha constituencies]], holding 18 road shows, 161 public meetings, and over 1,500 BJP meetings.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.livemint.com/elections/lok-sabha-elections/legwork-foot-soldiers-and-focus-on-its-social-schemes-behind-bjp-s-success-1558637200733.html |title=Legwork, foot soldiers and focus on its social schemes behind BJP's success |newspaper=Mint |date=24 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\nHe is often referred to as a modern-day [[Chanakya]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/lok-sabha-2019/story/amit-shah-bjp-s-chanakya-strategised-modi-wave-2-0-1532943-2019-05-23|title=Amit Shah: BJP's Chanakya who strategised and delivered Modi wave 2.0|date=23 May 2019|website=India Today|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> who had skillfully replaced the [[Nanda dynasty]] by the young [[Chandragupta Maurya]]. He himself is an admirer of Chanakya. Responding to the questions from a reporter about a portrait of Chanakya at his New Delhi residence in 2016, he said: \"[I admire] Chanakya because he was knowledgeable. His sutras are eternal. Economics, politics, the problem of governance are all there.\u201d The [[Bhagavata Purana]] is another of his favourite books, which he studied when he was in prison.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Union Cabinet Minister==\n===Minister of Home Affairs===\n{{update section|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:The Vice President and Chairman, Rajya Sabha, Shri M. Venkaiah Naidu administering the oath as Member, Rajya Sabha to Shri Amit Shah, at a Swearing-in Ceremony, at Parliament House, in New Delhi (cropped).jpg|thumb|Amit Shah takes oath with Ram Vilas Paswan beside him]]\nShah took oath as Cabinet Minister on 30 May 2019. He took office as [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]] on 1 June 2019.<ref>{{citation |title=PM Modi allocates portfolios. Full list of new ministers |url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/pm-modi-allocates-portfolios-full-list-of-new-ministers-1559288502067.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 May 2019 }}</ref> On 5 August 2019, Shah moved resolution to scrap Article 370 in the Rajya Sabha.,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kashmir-unrest-amit-shah-parliament-reservation-bill-amendment-artcle-370-1577275-2019-08-05|title=No Article 370 for Jammu & Kashmir, historic move by Modi govt|date=5 August 2019|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=5 August 2019}}</ref> and also reorganize the state with [[Jammu and Kashmir]] serving as one of the union territory and [[Ladakh]] region separated out as a separate union territory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/jammu-and-kashmir-crisis-live-updates-1564981600854.html|title=Jammu and Kashmir Live News: Article 370 to be revoked, J&K to be reorganised|date=5 August 2019|website=LiveMint}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2019, Shah declared in the Rajya Sabha of the Indian parliament that the [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC) will be implemented throughout the country.<ref name=\"Shah NRC IT\">{{cite news |title=Amit Shah: NRC to apply nationwide, no person of any religion should worry |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/amit-shah-nrc-rajya-sabha-1620810-2019-11-20 |accessdate=22 December 2019 |work=India Today |date=20 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, he introduced the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] bill, which grants Indian citizenship to religiously persecuted minority communities who migrated to the country before 2015 from the Muslim-majority countries of Pakistan, Bangladesh and Afghanistan. In [[North-East India]], people concerned about the impact of immigration on local culture and politics protested against the Act. Elsewhere, the opposition parties criticized the Act's exclusion of Muslims as detrimental to India's pluralism. Shah, however, insisted that that the bill was not anti-Muslim because it did not change the existing path to citizenship available for them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/india-parliament-passes-citizenship-bill-1.5392455 |title=India's parliament passes contentious citizenship bill |publisher=CBC News |date=20 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Electoral record ==\nSince 1989, Shah has fought 28 elections to various local bodies. As of 2019, he has never lost an election.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Year\n! Constituency\n! Result\n! Votes\n! % Votes\n! Source\n|-\n| [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]] ([[by-election]])\n| 1997\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 76,839\n| 56.10%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/ByeElection/ByeApril1997/S06/gj-64-la.html |title=Bye-Elections 1997: Sarkhej |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=27 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 1998\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 193,373\n| 69.81%\n| <ref name=\"rediff_1998_Sarkhej\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/election/gujarat/sarkhej.htm |title=Constituency Data - Summary: Sarkhej - 1998 |website=rediff.com |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2002 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 2002\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 288,327\n| 66.98%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/archive/Decse2002/pollupd/ac/states/s06/aconst64.htm |title=State Elections 2002: 64-Sarkhej Constituency of Gujarat |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2007 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 2007\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 407,659\n| 68.00%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/archive/Dec2007/pollupd/ac/states/s06/aconst64.htm |title=State Elections 2007: 64-Sarkhej Constituency of Gujarat |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2012 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 2012\n| [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]]\n| Won\n| 103,988\n| 69.19%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/ECI_Main/CI_2013/Gujaratl/45-Naranpura.pdf |title=Form-21E: 45-Naranpura |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2019 Indian general election|General Election]]\n| 2019\n| [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]]\n| Won\n|888,210\n|69.76%\n|\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nShah is married to Sonal Shah and the couple have a son named [[Jay Shah|Jay]]. Shah was very close to his mother, who died from an illness on 8 June 2010.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/><ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> People close to Shah have described him as someone who does not like to socialize much.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.asianage.com/india/shrewd-modi-loyalist-able-%E2%80%98manage-everything%E2%80%99-672 |title=Shrewd Modi loyalist able to 'manage everything' |author=Deepal Trivedi |date=23 July 2010 |newspaper=Asian Age }}</ref>  He has six sisters, two of whom live abroad in Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/report/ls-election-amit-shah-on-friday-wakes-up-late-eats-poha-chats-with-modi/20140516.htm|title=Exclusive! Amit Shah on Friday: Wakes up late, eats poha, chats with Modi|website=rediff.com|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> In September 2019, he  was successfully operated for lipoma at the backside of neck under local anaesthesia. After this minor surgery, he was  discharged.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/amit-shah-successfully-operated-for-lipoma-at-a-hospital-in-ahmedabad-5965286/ |title = Amit Shah undergoes operation for lipoma at Ahmedabad hospital|date = 5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n[[File:Prime Minister Narendra Modi visits Shauryanjali, a commemorative exhibition on the 1965 war.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Narendra Modi visits Shauryanjali, a commemorative exhibition on the 1965 war]]\nShah was accused of sidelining the police officers who testified against the Gujarat government in cases related to the fake encounters and the [[2002 Gujarat violence|2002 riots]]. Additional [[Director General of Police|DGP]] [[R. B. Sreekumar]], who gave evidence to the [[Nanavati-Shah commission]], was allegedly denied promotion. [[Rahul Sharma (Gujarat police)|Rahul Sharma]], who handed over phone records of police officers and politicians to the Commission, was charged with violating the [[Official Secrets Act]]. Additional DGP Kuldeep Sharma alleged that he had been moved from the police department to Gujarat State Sheep and Wool Development Corporation, after he accused Shah of taking a bribe of Rs 2.5 crore to bail out a conman who fraudulently withdrew Rs 1,600 crore from the Madhavpura Mercantile Cooperative Bank. Kuldeep Sharma was later made advisor to the central home ministry by the Congress government. His brother Pradeep Sharma was imprisoned in Gujarat from 2010 to 2011 on corruption charges. The brothers claim that the Gujarat Government was harassing them.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Shah has also been accused of manipulating the electoral constituency delimitation exercise in Gujarat to favour BJP.<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\"/>\n\nOn 11 December 2019 federal US commission on International Religious Freedom (USCIRF) asked the US administration to consider imposing sanctions against Home Minister Amit Shah if the Indian parliament passes the Citizenship Amendment Bill 2019. USCIRF in its statement said, \"CAB is a dangerous turn in the wrong direction; it runs counter to India\u2019s rich history of secular pluralism and the Indian Constitution, which guarantees equality before the law regardless of faith\". The commission chaired by Republican Tony Perkins said CAB \"enshrines a pathway to citizenship for immigrants that specifically excludes Muslims, setting a legal criterion for citizenship based on religion\". The external affairs ministry was quick in issuing a counter-statement in response to USCIRF by saying that it was not based on facts and the bill was to grant citizenship to persecuted religious minorities who arrived in India and does not aim to strip citizenship<ref name=\"Sanctions on Amit Shah\">{{cite web |last1=Amit Shah |first1=sanctions against |title=Sanctions against Amit Shah over CAB |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/sanctions-against-amit-shah-over-cab-rajnath-singh-jaishankar-may-take-up-issue-in-washington-dc/articleshow/72465942.cms |website=The Economic Times |publisher=The Economic Times |accessdate=8 March 2020 |ref=Amit Shah sanctions}}</ref>\n\n==== Snoopgate ====\nIn 2013, Shah was accused of having ordered illegal surveillance on a woman in 2009, during his tenure as a home minister. The investigative websites [[Cobrapost]] and Gulail released a set of taped audio conversations between Shah and police officer GL Singhal. The tapes had been submitted to the CBI in the [[Ishrat Jahan]] fake encounter case, and were leaked to these portals. The calls detail how the state machinery was used to surveil the woman and the IAS officer Pradeep Sharma (who was suspended by the Gujarat Government). Both Singhal and Shah repeatedly refer to a higher authority as ''Saheb'', believed to be the Chief Minister Narendra Modi.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cobrapost.com/index.php/news-detail?nid=3969&cid=23 |title=News Detail |publisher=Cobrapost.com |date= |accessdate=4 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231084530/http://www.cobrapost.com/index.php/news-detail?nid=3969&cid=23 |archive-date=31 December 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Shah denied all the accusations against him, calling them political propaganda by his opponents.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> BJP's political opponents demanded a probe in this ''Snoopgate'' case. However, in May 2014, the woman approached the Supreme Court and stated that the surveillance on her was based on a \"personal request\", and she was thankful to the Gujarat government for ensuring her safety. She requested the court to block any investigation, stating that it would violate her privacy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/elections/article/election-2014/snoopgate-thankful-for-surveillance-woman-tells-supreme-court-519233 |title=Snoopgate: 'Thankful' for Surveillance, Woman Tells Supreme Court |author=Deepshikha Ghosh |date=6 May 2014 |publisher=NDTV }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.amitshah.co.in/ Official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[L. K. Advani]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]] |years=2019 \u2013 Present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rajnath Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=30 May 2019 \u2013 Present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rajnath Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Second Narendra Modi Cabinet}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Amit}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Gujarat University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Indian Vaishnavites]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Alliance candidates in the 2019 Indian general election]]\n[[Category:Narendra Modi ministry]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of India]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Internal Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Indian prisoners and detainees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Minister of Home Affairs (India)}}\n{{for|other people with the same name|Amit Shah (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2014}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| birth_name = Amit Anilchandra Shah\n| image = [[File:Amit shah official portrait.jpg|220px|border]]\n| image_size = 220px\n| Caption = \n| office = [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n| predecessor = [[Rajnath Singh]]\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start = 30 May 2019\n| office1 = [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|Chairperson of the National Democratic Alliance]]\n| predecessor1 = [[L. K. Advani]]\n| successor1 = \n| term_start1 = 9 July 2014\n| office2 = [[List of Presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President of the Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Rajnath Singh]]\n| successor2 = [[Jagat Prakash Nadda]]\n| term_start2 = 9 July 2014\n| term_end2 = 20 January 2020\n| office3 = [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|Member of Parliament]]<br>[[Lok Sabha]]\n| majority3 = 5,57,014 (43.38%)\n| term_start3 = 23 May 2019\n| predecessor3 = [[L. K. Advani]]\n| constituency3 = [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]]\n| office4 = [[Member of parliament, Rajya Sabha|Member of Parliament]]<br>[[Rajya Sabha]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Dilip Pandya]]\n| successor4 = [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]]\n| constituency4 = [[Gujarat]]\n| term_start4 = 19 August 2017\n| term_end4 = 29 May 2019\n| office5 = [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly|Member of the Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start5 = 2012\n| term_end5 = 2017\n| constituency5 = [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]]\n| predecessor5 = ''office established''\n| successor5 = [[Kaushik Patel (politician)|Kaushik Patel]]\n| term_start6 = 1997\n| term_end6 = 2012\n| successor6 = ''office abolished''\n| predecessor6 = [[Harishchandra Patel|Harishchandra Lavjibhai Patel]]\n| constituency6 = [[Sarkhej (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sarkhej]]\n| office7 = [[Minister of State]], [[Government of Gujarat]]\n| term_start7 = 2002\n| term_end7 = 2012\n| 1blankname7 = Departments\n| 1namedata7 = Home, Law and Justice, Prison, Border Security, Civil Defence, Excise, Home Guards, Transport, Prohibition, Gram Rakshak Dal, Police Housing, Legislative and Parliamentary Affairs\n| 2blankname7 = Chief Minister\n| 2namedata7 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|10|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"IE_2014_prepares\"/>\n| birth_place = [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| spouse = Sonal Shah\n| children = [[Jay Shah]]\n| alma_mater = [[Gujarat University]] ([[B.Sc.]])\n| website = {{URL|www.amitshah.co.in}}\n}}\n'''Amit Anilchandra Shah'''<ref name=\"Jagran\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jagranjosh.com/general-knowledge/amit-shah-biography-1558610444-1|title=Amit Shah Union Home Minister of India 2019 : Age, Family, Political Life and Interesting Facts|date=16 August 2019}}</ref> (born 22 October 1964) is an Indian politician serving as [[Minister of Home Affairs(India)|Minister of Home Affairs]] who has served as [[List of Presidents of the Bharatiya Janata Party|President]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) from 2014 to 2020. He was elected to the lower House of Parliament the [[Lok Sabha]] in the [[2019 Indian general election]] from [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]]. He was earlier elected  as a  member of the  upper House of Parliament the [[Rajya Sabha]] from [[Gujarat]] in 2017. He also became the youngest serving full-time [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Home Minister]] at an age of 54.<ref name=\"Jagran\"/> He is the chief strategist of the BJP and a close aide to [[Narendra Modi]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/amit-shah-bjps-chanakya-who-delivered-modi-wave-2-0/articleshow/69465902.cms | title=Amit Shah: BJP's 'Chanakya' who delivered Modi Wave 2.0 | publisher=[[The Times of India]] | date=23 May 2019 | accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/lok-sabha-2019/story/amit-shah-bjp-s-chanakya-strategised-modi-wave-2-0-1532943-2019-05-23 | title=Amit Shah: BJP's Chanakya who strategised and delivered Modi wave 2.0 | publisher=India Today | date=23 May 2019 | accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his college days Shah was a member of [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad|ABVP]], student wing of the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|RSS]]. At the age of 18, he secured a position in the ABVP, and joined the BJP in 1987. Shah was first elected in Gujarat as the [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] for a seat partly covering [[Ahmedabad]], [[Sarkhej (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sarkhej]] in 1997 (a by-election) holding it in 1998, 2002 and 2007 until the seat's 2008 dissolution, then for nearby [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]], from [[2012 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2012]]-2017. He is a close associate of Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and held executive portfolios in the [[Government of Gujarat|state government]] during Modi's tenure as its Chief Minister.\n\nShah was the BJP's in-charge for India's largest and politically most crucial state, [[Uttar Pradesh]], during the [[2014 Lok Sabha elections]]. The BJP and its allies swept the state, registering their best performance, by winning 73 out of 80 seats. As a result, Shah rose to national prominence and was appointed as the party's national president in July 2014.<ref name=\"IT_new_2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/20140728-rahul-kanwal-on-the-man-behind-the-reputation-amit-shah-bjp-804608-2014-07-17 |title=Inside the mind of Amit Shah: All eyes on new BJP chief as party gears up for battle in five states |date=17 July 2014 |publisher=India Today }}</ref>\n\nHe has played an organising and membership-promotional role in elections of many states since 2014. In his initial two years, the BJP achieved success in Legislative Assembly elections in [[2014 Maharashtra Legislative Assembly election|Maharashtra]], [[2014 Haryana Legislative Assembly election|Haryana]], [[2014 Jammu and Kashmir Legislative Assembly election|Jammu & Kashmir]], [[2014 Jharkhand Legislative Assembly election|Jharkhand]] in 2014 and in [[Assam]] but lost ground in [[2015 Delhi Legislative Assembly election|Delhi]] and the large eastern state of [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|Bihar]] in 2015.\n\nHe was in 2017 partly credited with the party landslides in [[2017 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|Uttar Pradesh]], [[2017 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|Uttarakhand]] and the party's modern heartland state of [[2017 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/elections/gujarat-2017/live-updates-2017-gujarat-legislative-assembly-election-results/article21830220.ece|title=Gujarat Assembly election results: Counting ends as BJP closes out Gujarat with 99 seats; Congress claims 77|last=Desk|first=The Hindu Net|date=18 December 2017|work=The Hindu|access-date=27 August 2018|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> in which year was marked the party's strong debut in much smaller [[2017 Manipur Legislative Assembly election|Manipur]], but the [[Shiromani Akali Dal|Akali]]-BJP alliance lost power in considerably larger [[2017 Punjab Legislative Assembly election|Punjab]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/punjab-election-result-2017-triangular-battle-between-akali-dal-bjp-congress-aap-1668526|title=Punjab Election Result 2017: Congress' Amarinder Singh Defeats Akali Dal-BJP, AAP - Highlights|work=NDTV.com|access-date=27 August 2018}}</ref> In 2018 the party lost power in the states of [[2018 Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly election|Chhattisgarh]], [[2018 Rajasthan Legislative Assembly election|Rajasthan]] and [[2018 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|Madhya Pradesh]]. The next year, BJP won 303 seats to get majority in the [[2019 Indian general election]], making Shah the most successful BJP President ever.<ref name=\"ET_most_successful\">{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/amit-shah-in-new-role-after-being-most-successful-bjp-chief/articleshow/69584774.cms |title=Amit Shah in new role after being most successful BJP chief |date=30 May 2019 |newspaper=Economic Times }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nShah was born in [[Mumbai]] on 22 October 1964.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/politics/amit-shah-an-organisation-man-at-helm-114071000099_1.html |title=Amit Shah: An organisation man at helm |author=Premal Balan |date=10 July 2014 |newspaper=Business Standard }}</ref> He came from a [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] [[Hindu]] [[Vaishnava]] family who were [[Baniya]]s.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/i-am-a-hindu-vaishnav-not-jain-amit-shah-1833945|title=\"I Am A Hindu Vaishnav, Not Jain\": Amit Shah|website=NDTV.com|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|quote=Amit Shah, himself a baniya |url=https://www.newsclick.in/amit-shah-borrowed-phrase-jinnah-when-he-dubbed-gandhi-chatur-bania|first=Shamsul|last=Islam|date=14 June 2017|publisher=Newsclick|title=Amit Shah Borrowed a Phrase from Jinnah when he Dubbed Gandhi a 'Chatur Bania'}}</ref> His great grandfather was the Nagarseth of the small [[Mansa, Gujarat#History|state of Mansa]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/amit-shah-the-strategist-of-bjp-s-india-game-plan/story-Fr0sSiYHtTwhVxKBsjapsI.html|title=The 'Shah' of BJP's game plan who wants to alter India's political culture|date=16 July 2016|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> His father Anil Chandra Shah, a businessman from [[Mansa, Gujarat|Mansa]], owned a successful [[polyvinyl chloride|PVC]] [[plastic pipework|pipe]] business.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He did his schooling in [[Mehsana]] and moved to [[Ahmedabad]] to study [[biochemistry]] at CU Shah Science College. He graduated with a [[B.Sc.]] degree in biochemistry, and then worked for his father's business.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He also worked as a stockbroker and in co-operative banks in Ahmedabad.<ref name=\"rediff_2010_fall\">{{cite news |url=http://news.rediff.com/special/2010/jul/24/what-amit-shahs-fall-really-means.htm |title=What Amit Shah's fall really means |author=Sheela Bhatt |website=rediff.com |date=28 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nShah was involved with the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] since childhood, participating in the neighbourhood ''shakhas'' (branches) as a boy. He formally became an RSS ''swayamsevak'' (volunteer) during his college days in Ahmedabad.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> He first met Narendra Modi in 1982 through Ahmedabad RSS circles.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\">{{cite news |url=http://www.openthemagazine.com/article/india/his-master-s-mind |title=His Master's Mind |publisher=Open |author=PR Ramesh |date=11 April 2014 }}</ref> At that time, Modi was an RSS ''pracharak'' (propagator), working as in-charge of youth activities in city.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\n== Early political career ==\nShah started his political career as a leader of the student wing of the RSS, the [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad]], in 1983.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/><ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\">{{cite news |title = Who is Amit Shah? |url=https://www.ndtv.com/people/who-is-amit-shah-525154 |publisher=NDTV |date=12 June 2013}}</ref> He joined BJP in 1987, one year before Modi joined the party.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He became an activist of BJP's youth wing [[Bharatiya Janata Yuva Morcha]] (BJYM) in 1987. He then gradually rose in the BJYM hierarchy, holding various posts including that of ward secretary, [[taluka]] secretary, state secretary, vice-president, and general secretary.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> He came into limelight for his excellent management when he was the election campaign manager for [[Lal Krishna Advani]] in Gandhinagar during the [[1991 Indian general election|1991 Lok Sabha elections]].<ref name=\"IE_2014_prepares\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bjp-union-home-ministry-amit-shah-1539468-2019-05-31 | title=From sticking bills for BJP to managing Union home ministry: Rise and rise of Amit Shah | publisher=India Today | work=Prabhash K Dutta | date=31 May 2019 | accessdate=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, BJP formed its first government in Gujarat, with [[Keshubhai Patel]] as the Chief Minister. At that time, BJP's main rival [[Indian National Congress]] was highly influential in rural Gujarat. Modi and Shah worked together to decimate Congress in the rural areas. Their strategy was to find the second most influential leader in every village, and get him or her to join BJP. They created a network of 8,000 influential rural leaders who had lost elections to the ''pradhan'' (village chief) post in various villages.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/>\n\nModi and Shah used the same strategy to reduce Congress' influence over the state's powerful [[co-operative]]s, which play an important role in the state's economy. In 1999, Shah was elected as the president of Ahmedabad District Cooperative Bank (ADCB), the biggest cooperative bank in India. In Gujarat, such elections had traditionally been won on the [[Indian caste system|caste]] considerations, and the co-operative banks had traditionally been controlled by [[Patel]]s, [[Gaderia]]s and [[Kshatriya]]s. Despite not belonging to any of these castes, Shah won the election. At that time, the bank was on the verge of collapsing, having accumulated losses of {{INR}} 36 [[crore]]. Shah turned around the bank's fortune within a year's time: the next year, the bank registered a profit of {{INR}} 27 crore. By 2014, the bank's profit had increased to around {{INR}} 250 crore.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Shah also ensured that 11 of the Bank's 22 directors were BJP loyalists.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nModi and Shah also sought to reduce the Congress hold over sports bodies in the state.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Shah served as the president of Gujarat State Chess Association.<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/> In 2009, he became the vice-president of the cash-rich [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] (GCA), when Narendra Modi served as its president.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> In 2014, after Modi became [[Prime Minister of India]], Shah became the president of GCA.\n\nModi, who had become a general secretary in the party's state unit by the early 1990s, used his influence to get bigger roles for Shah. He convinced Patel to appoint Shah as the chairman of the [[Gujarat State Financial Corporation]], a public sector financial institution which finances small and medium-scale enterprises. After [[Shankersinh Vaghela]] and some other leaders complained about Modi's growing clout in the Gujarat government, the party leadership moved Modi out of Gujarat, to the BJP headquarters in Delhi. During this time (1995-2001), Shah served as Modi's informer in Gujarat.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nIn 1997, Modi lobbied to get Shah a BJP ticket for the [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]] by-election in [[Sarkhej]].<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\">{{cite news |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/The-importance-of-Amit-Shah/articleshow/33378596.cms |title=The importance of Amit Shah |newspaper=Mumbai Mirror |date=7 April 2014 }}</ref> Shah became an MLA in February 1997 after winning the by-election.<ref name=\"Andy2014\">{{cite book |author=Andy Marino |title=Narendra Modi: A Political Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ylIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT76 |date=8 April 2014 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |isbn=978-93-5136-218-0 |pages=76\u2013}}</ref> He retained his seat in the 1998 Assembly elections.<ref name=\"rediff_1998_Sarkhej\"/>\n\n== Gujarat's minister==\n[[File:PM Modii addresses a BJP National Council Meet.jpg|thumb|PM Modi addresses a BJP National Council Meet]]\nIn October 2001, BJP replaced Keshubhai Patel with Narendra Modi as the chief minister of Gujarat, following allegations of inefficient administration. Over the next few years, Modi and Shah gradually sidelined their political rivals.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nShah contested the [[2002 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2002 Assembly election]] from the [[Sarkhej]] constituency in Ahmedabad. He won by the highest margin among all candidates: 158,036 votes. In the [[2007 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2007 Assembly election]], he won from Sarkhej again, improving his margin of victory.<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/>\n\nDuring Narendra Modi's twelve-year tenure as the Gujarat CM, Shah emerged as one of the most powerful leaders in Gujarat. After winning the 2002 elections, he became the youngest minister in the Modi government, and was given multiple portfolios.<ref name=\"IE_2014_prepares\">{{cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/2013/jul/07/In-UP-Shah-prepares-for-Modi-ahead-of-2014-battle-494331.html |title=In UP, Shah prepares for Modi ahead of 2014 battle |date=7 July 2013 |newspaper=Indian Express |author=Subhash Mishra and Pratul Sharma}}</ref> At one time, he held 12 portfolios: Home, Law and Justice, Prison, Border Security, Civil Defence, Excise, Transport, Prohibition, Home Guards, Gram Rakshak Dal, Police Housing, and Legislative and Parliamentary Affairs.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\">{{cite news |url=https://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/organiser |title=The Organiser |author=Poornima Joshi |publisher=Caravan |date=1 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the Congress-led Central Government announced its intention to repeal the [[Prevention of Terrorism Act, 2002|Prevention of Terrorism Act]], calling it regressive. Shah piloted the [[Gujarat Control of Organised Crime Act|Gujarat Control of Organised Crime]] (Amendment) Bill through Gujarat state assembly amid an opposition walk-out.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/gujarat-keeps-a-terror-law-spare/cid/737976 | location=Calcutta, India | work=The Telegraph | title=Gujarat keeps a terror law spare | date=3 June 2004}}</ref>\n\nShah also played an important role in convincing the Narendra Modi government to pass the [[Gujarat Freedom of Religion Bill|Gujarat Freedom of Religion Act]], which made religious conversions difficult in Hindu-majority Gujarat. His opponents argued that the Act went against the rights guaranteed by the [[Indian Constitution]], but Shah defended the bill, calling it a measure against forced conversions. His efforts in getting the bill passed impressed the senior leadership of RSS.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\" />\n\n==Politics==\n\n=== Police encounter cases ===\n[[File:Amit Shah and Udit Raj.jpg|thumb|Amit Shah and Udit Raj]]\nIn 2010, Shah was accused of having orchestrated the extrajudicial killings of criminal <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/who-was-sohrabuddin-sheikh-424777|title = Who was Sohrabuddin Sheikh| publisher=NDTV.com | date = 27 July 2010 }}</ref> [[Sohrabuddin Sheikh]], his wife Kauser Bi and his criminal associate [[Tulsiram Prajapati]]. According to the [[Central Bureau of Investigation|CBI]], Sohrabuddin had been harassing some [[marble]] traders of Rajasthan, by demanding hefty [[protection racket|protection]] money. CBI claimed that two of these marble traders paid Shah to eliminate Sohrabuddin. He, along with the police officers [[Deputy inspector general of police|DIG]] [[D. G. Vanzara|DG Vanzara]] and [[Superintendent of police (India)|SP]] Rajkumar Pandian, allegedly hatched a plan to kill Sohrabuddin. In 2004, [[List of police ranks in India|DCP]] Abhay Chudasama pressured Sohrabuddin and Tulsiram to fire at the office of two builder brothers - Raman Patel and Dashrath Patel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-sohrabuddin-case-how-patel-bros-were-fleeced-1420791 |author=Nikunj Soni |title=Sohrabuddin case: How Patel bros were 'fleeced' |date=9 August 2010 |newspaper=DNA }}</ref> This was done so that a fresh criminal case could be registered against Sohrabuddin and Tulsiram. The next year, the police picked up Sohrabuddin, Kausar Bi and Tulsiram, and took them to a farmhouse near Ahmedabad. Sohrabuddin was killed in a staged attack, with Vanzara claiming that he was a [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] operative. Kausar Bi was also killed and cremated for being a witness. Tulsiram was initially let off, as he was an informer of Vanzara. He was eliminated later, after Sohrabuddin's death was exposed as an extrajudicial killing by a journalist. CBI claimed that Shah had transferred Vanzara to various places in order to facilitate these killings.<ref name=\"rediff_2007_cracked\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/apr/25spec.htm |title=The journalist who cracked Gujarat fake encounter case |date=25 April 2007 |website=rediff.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/cop-transfers-part-of-shah-plan/story-cFpY9WJFOTx9Los8qmjbGL.html |title=Cop transfers part of Shah plan |publisher=Hindustan Times |author=Abhishek Sharan |date=26 July 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018155653/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/Cop-transfers-part-of-Shah-plan/Article1-577692.aspx |archivedate=18 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nVanzara and several other officers were arrested in the case. As proof of Shah's involvement in the crimes, the CBI presented phone call records, which showed that Shah had been in touch with the accused police officers when the victims were in their illegal custody. It also presented videotapes of Patel brothers' conversations with two of Shah's associates at Ahmedabad District Cooperative Bank (ADCB). In the tape, ADCB Director Yashpal Chudasama and its Chairman [[Ajay Patel]] can be seen asking the brothers not to involve Shah's name in the case. Yashpal Chudasama is the brother of the accused police officer Abhay Chudasama. According to CBI, Abhay used to run an extortion racket, with Sohrabuddin as his henchman.<ref name=\"IBNLive_2010_proof\">{{cite news |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/cbi-proof-against-shah-sohrabuddin-tapes/127540-37.html |title=CBI 'proof' against Shah: Sohrabuddin tapes |date=26 July 2010 |author=Bhupendra Chaubey |publisher=CNN-IBN }}</ref> The Patel brothers, who had several criminal cases against them, also spoke against Shah. They claimed that the police had falsely implicated them into various cases between 2001-2005 in order to extort money from them. They also claimed that Vanzara made them talk to Shah over phone, and Shah threatened them into giving a statement against Sohrabuddin and Tulsiram. They further stated that, in 2006, [[Ajay Patel]] and Abhay Chudasama called them again on behalf of Shah, asking them to give certain statements to CBI.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/he-(amit-shah)-smiled-and-said-sohrabuddin-had-himself-closed-the-option-of-keeping-himself-alive.../658769/0 |title=He (Amit Shah) smiled and said Sohrabuddin had himself closed the option of keeping himself alive... |date=24 November 2011 |newspaper=Indian Express }}</ref>\n\nShah dismissed all the accusations against him as politically motivated. He pointed out that during his tenure as the Home Minister, Gujarat was one of the states with minimum number of police encounters in the country. He stated that he kept in touch with the police officers on the phone in the normal course of his duties as the home minister.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-11-14/news/44075365_1_sadiq-jamal-ishrat-jahan-amit-shah |title=CBI to file crucial charge-sheets in Gujarat fake encounters' case |author=Aman Sharma |newspaper=Economic times |date=14 November 2013 }}</ref> He accused the Congress of misusing CBI, and claimed that only the encounter cases in Gujarat were being scrutinised when the rest of the country had witnessed around 1500 encounters during the same period.<ref name=\"rediff_2013_waiting\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-exclusive-amit-shah-interview-people-are-waiting-to-vote-for-modi/20131008.htm#3 |title=Encounter cases are politically motivated; non-Gujarat encounters are never scrutinised |date=8 October 2013 |author=Sheela Bhatt |website=rediff.com }}</ref> He said that if CBI had any solid evidence against him, it would have been able to frame charges against him.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> In 2010, Police Commissioner Geeta Johri, who first investigated the case, claimed that CBI was pressurizing her to falsely implicate Shah in the Sohrabuddin case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/cbi-putting-pressure-on-me-geeta-johri/article599990.ece |title=CBI putting pressure on me: Geeta Johri |author=J. Venkatesan |newspaper=The Hindu |date=29 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nDG Vanzara was also accused in the [[Ishrat Jahan]] fake encounter case, but the CBI gave Shah a clean sheet in the case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/CBI-clean-chit-for-Amit-Shah-in-Ishrat-Jahan-encounter-case/articleshow/34784569.cms |title=CBI clean chit for Amit Shah in Ishrat Jahan encounter case |date=7 May 2014 |newspaper=The Times of India }}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest and exile ===\nShah was arrested on 25 July 2010 in connection with the [[Death of Sohrabuddin Sheikh|Sohrabuddin case]]. He was [[Indian Penal Code|charged]] with the murder, extortion, and kidnapping among other charges. At one time, Shah was considered as one of the main contenders for the Gujarat Chief Minister's post. However, his political career was hurt by the arrest. Many leaders in the Gujarat government distanced themselves from him. His fellow ministers considered him as an autocratic person, who did not have good relations with his colleagues.<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/>\n\nWhen Shah applied for bail, the CBI raised concerns that he would use his political power to prevent justice from taking its course.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> The [[Gujarat High Court]] granted him bail three months after his arrest, on Friday, 29 October 2010. However, the next day, when the courts were closed, Justice [[Aftab Alam (judge)|Aftab Alam]] took a petition at his residence to bar him from entering Gujarat.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Shah was thus forcibly exiled from the state from 2010 to 2012.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> He and his wife moved to a room in Gujarat Bhavan, Delhi.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> Later, the Supreme Court canceled his bail on a CBI plea. In September 2012, the Supreme Court granted him bail, and allowed him to return to Gujarat. He then contested and won the [[2012 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|2012 Assembly election]] from [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]] constituency (the Sarkhej constituency had ceased to exist after delimitation).<ref name=\"NDTV_2013_who\"/>\n\n=\n\n== Rise in national politics ==\nAfter Narendra Modi became the Prime Ministerial candidate of BJP, Shah's influence also increased in the party. The two have been accused of sidelining other BJP leaders such as [[Lal Krishna Advani]], [[Sushma Swaraj]], [[Murli Manohar Joshi]] and [[Jaswant Singh]].<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> By this time, Shah had gained recognition as an excellent election campaign manager, and had been dubbed a \"modern-day [[Chanakya]] and master strategist\".<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/amit-shah-set-for-bigger-role-if-bjp-wins/article5903327.ece Amit Shah set for bigger role if BJP wins], Vinay Kumar, 12 April 2014</ref> Shah was appointed as a BJP general secretary, and was given charge of [[Uttar Pradesh]] (UP). He was chosen not by Modi, but by Rajnath Singh, who had been impressed by the skills that Shah displayed in wresting control of various Congress-controlled organizations in Gujarat.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/> The decision did not go down well with many in the party, who saw him as a liability owing to the criminal charges against him. Political analysts such as [[Shekhar Gupta]] termed the decision as a blunder.<ref name=\"Shekhar2014\">{{cite book |author=Shekhar Gupta |title=Anticipating India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TipIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT369 |date=8 April 2014 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |isbn=978-93-5136-256-2 |page=369 }}</ref>\n\n=== Uttar Pradesh general elections ===\nShah's political career, which had declined after his arrest in 2010, revived after BJP's victory in the [[2014 Indian general election|2014 general election]]. In UP, where Shah was the in-charge, BJP and its allies won 73 out of 80 seats. Shah had been made in charge of BJP's UP campaigning on 12 June 2013, less than a year before the elections.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Since February 2012, Shah had spent considerable time in UP, trying to understand the reasons for the [[Samajwadi Party]]'s winning performance in the [[2012 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|2012 UP Assembly elections]]. Shah realised that the voters were dissatisfied with the Samajwadi Party, which he believed had failed to keep its election promises after the win. He also took advantage of the [[Other Backward Classes|OBC]] voters' displeasure with the UP government's decision to create 4.5% [[reservation in India|reservation]] for the minorities within the 27% OBC quota in government jobs and education.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/>\n\nShah personally oversaw the candidate selection, emphasizing on the candidate's local clout and winning potential as the only criteria for selection, as opposed to the candidate's party loyalty or ideology. His team estimated that only 35% of the BJP's traditional supporters had actually voted in the UP elections. Therefore, he focused on door-to-door campaigning at the [[voting booth|booth]]-level. He set up a 7-to-10 member management committee for each of the 140,000 voting booths in the state. For each booth, his team collated lists of voters and reached out to them.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Shah's team used 450 GPS-enabled mobile vans (\"video [[Ratha|raths]]\") to reach out to the masses in remote areas, where media reach was negligible.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140518/commentary-op-ed/article/sunday-interview-amit-shah |title=Sunday Interview: We had 450 video raths with GPS and I'd get feedback on my mobile, says Amit Shah |newspaper=Deccan Chronicle | date=18 May 2014 |author=Yojna Gosai }}</ref> Shah personally covered 76 out of 80 Lok Sabha constituencies. He also insisted on Modi contesting election from [[Varanasi]].<ref name=\"Outlook_2014_Feast\">{{cite news |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Judgement-Day-Feast-For-The-Shah-Of-Shahs/290749 |title=Judgement Day Feast For The Shah Of Shahs |author=Prarthna Gahilote |publisher=Outlook |date=26 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nShah convinced Modi to utilize RSS volunteers for grassroots campaigning, which proved highly beneficial for BJP.<ref name=\"Outlook_2014_Feast\"/> Although RSS officially did not get involved in electioneering, Shah used its volunteers to mobilize and monitor the campaigners. For example, the RSS volunteers would cross-check a BJP worker's claims of having targeted a given number of households.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Shah also helped organize \"mega rallies\" for Modi. Like other major political parties, BJP provisioned one van per village to transport people to the rally venue. However, unlike others, Shah decided that BJP would not provide money for hiring these vehicles. Instead, he declared that the party workers organizing the transportation would be made the leaders of the BJP units in their respective villages. This strategy ensured that a number of local village leaders developed a stake in Modi's victory.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/>\n\nCritics accused Shah of trying to polarize the UP voters along the religious lines. While visiting [[Ayodhya]] for a meeting with the party's local committee, he raised the [[Ram Janmabhoomi]] temple issue (see [[Ayodhya dispute]]). BJP fielded three candidates accused of inciting violence during the [[2013 Muzaffarnagar riots]]. These were seen as attempts to target the party's [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] base.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> An [[First Information Report|FIR]] was registered against Shah for a speech in Muzaffarnagar, where he urged the voters to seek \"revenge\" through their votes.<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\"/> He also took advantage of Shia Muslim antipathy towards Sunni Muslims in [[Lucknow]].<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21627719-narendra-modi-relies-most-two-men-who-could-hardly-be-less-alike-enablers The enablers: Narendra Modi relies most on two men who could hardly be less alike], economist.com.</ref>\n\nShah also played an important role in BJP's election campaigning strategy outside Uttar Pradesh. He focused on building Modi's image as a strong leader. At times, he opposed even Modi on several strategic campaigning issues. For example, when Modi praised his opponent and prospective post-poll ally [[Mamata Banerjee]], Shah insisted that BJP must not divert from the \"Modi-versus-all\" tactic.<ref name=\"Outlook_2014_Feast\"/> Shah was also responsible for forging BJP's alliances with regional parties like [[Pattali Makkal Katchi]].<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\"/>\n\n== BJP President  ==\n[[File:Modi congratulates Amit Shah as he becomes BJP President.jpg|thumb|Modi congratulates Amit Shah as he becomes BJP President]]\nIn July 2014, BJP's Central Parliamentary Board unanimously approved Shah's appointment as president of the party.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-07-09/news/51247833_1_bjp-president-rajnath-singh-nitin-gadkari |title=BJP strategist & Narendra Modi's confidant Amit Shah appointed party president |date=9 July 2014 |newspaper=Economic Times}}</ref> He was reelected BJP President unanimously on 24 January 2016.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/amit-shah-reelected-bjp-president/article8147827.ece Amit Shah re-elected BJP president]. The Hindu, 25 January 2016.</ref>\n\nAfter becoming party president, Shah started an aggressive membership drive and by March 2015 BJP claimed 100 million members.<ref>{{citation |title=BJP becomes largest political party in the world |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/BJP-becomes-largest-political-party-in-the-world/articleshow/46739025.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=30 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Move Over, CCP: India's BJP Now the World's Largest Political Party |url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/04/move-over-ccp-indias-bjp-now-the-worlds-largest-political-party |work=[[The Diplomat]] |date=9 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nUnder his leadership during 2014-16, BJP achieved success in Legislative Assembly elections in [[2014 Maharashtra Legislative Assembly election|Maharashtra]], [[2014 Haryana Legislative Assembly election|Haryana]], [[2014 Jammu and Kashmir Legislative Assembly election|Jammu & Kashmir]], [[2014 Jharkhand Legislative Assembly election|Jharkhand]]  and [[2016 Assam Legislative Assembly election|Assam]], but lost the elections in [[2015 Delhi Legislative Assembly election|Delhi]] and [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|Bihar]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/comment-bihar-elections-2015-has-amit-shah-lost-his-inner-chanakya-2143597 |title=Bihar Elections 2015: Has BJP President Amit Shah lost his inner Chanakya? |author=Arghya Roy |newspaper=DNA |date=9 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nShah also spearheaded campaigning in the 2017 assembly elections, which gave BJP resounding success in [[2017 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|Uttar Pradesh]] and [[2017 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|Uttarakhand]], meaning the party won its greatest run in percentage terms in recent state assembly elections: 325 seats out of 403.<ref>{{citation |title=Uttar Pradesh election results: How BJP chief Amit Shah crafted a winning strategy for PM Modi |url=http://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uttar-pradesh-election-results-how-bjp-chief-amit-shah-crafted-a-winning-strategy-for-pm-modi/articleshow/57589801.cms |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=11 March 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Narendra Modi's B.J.P. Party Wins Big in Uttar Pradesh, India's Largest State |url=https://mobile.nytimes.com/2017/03/11/world/asia/narendra-modis-party-wins-big-in-uttar-pradesh-indias-largest-state.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=11 March 2017 }}</ref> BJP made some headway into [[2017 Manipur Legislative Assembly election|Manipur]].<ref>{{citation |title=How Amit Shah won U.P., one booth at a time |url=http://www.thehindu.com/elections/uttar-pradesh-2017/how-amit-shah-won-up-one-booth-at-a-time/article17448474.ece |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=11 March 2017 |last1=Hebbar |first1=Nistula }}</ref> Under his stewardship, the BJP has also won 2017 Gujarat Legislative Assembly polls for a record six times and wrested power from the [[Indian National Congress|INC]] during the 2017 Himachal Pradesh Legislative Assembly polls. In March 2018, BJP won first time in the left-ruled northeastern state of Tripura with a two-thirds majority. BJP also made gains in Nagaland and Meghalaya and formed government in both states with its allies.\n\nIn 2018, Shah said millions of \"illegal infiltrators\" have entered the country like \"termites\" and should be \"uprooted\": \"Should they be thrown out or not? Millions of infiltrators have entered our country and are eating the country like termites. Should we not uproot them?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/09/bjp-chief-slammed-calling-bangladesh-migrants-termites-180924155313048.html|date=24 September 2018|title=BJP chief slammed for calling Bangladeshi migrants 'termites'|work=Al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\nShah led BJP to victory in the [[2019 Indian general election]], becoming the most successful BJP President ever, in the process.<ref name=\"ET_most_successful\"/> During the election campaign, he visited 312 of the 543 [[List of constituencies of the Lok Sabha|Lok Sabha constituencies]], holding 18 road shows, 161 public meetings, and over 1,500 BJP meetings.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.livemint.com/elections/lok-sabha-elections/legwork-foot-soldiers-and-focus-on-its-social-schemes-behind-bjp-s-success-1558637200733.html |title=Legwork, foot soldiers and focus on its social schemes behind BJP's success |newspaper=Mint |date=24 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\nHe is often referred to as a modern-day [[Chanakya]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/lok-sabha-2019/story/amit-shah-bjp-s-chanakya-strategised-modi-wave-2-0-1532943-2019-05-23|title=Amit Shah: BJP's Chanakya who strategised and delivered Modi wave 2.0|date=23 May 2019|website=India Today|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> who had skillfully replaced the [[Nanda dynasty]] by the young [[Chandragupta Maurya]]. He himself is an admirer of Chanakya. Responding to the questions from a reporter about a portrait of Chanakya at his New Delhi residence in 2016, he said: \"[I admire] Chanakya because he was knowledgeable. His sutras are eternal. Economics, politics, the problem of governance are all there.\u201d The [[Bhagavata Purana]] is another of his favourite books, which he studied when he was in prison.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Union Cabinet Minister==\n===Minister of Home Affairs===\n{{update section|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:The Vice President and Chairman, Rajya Sabha, Shri M. Venkaiah Naidu administering the oath as Member, Rajya Sabha to Shri Amit Shah, at a Swearing-in Ceremony, at Parliament House, in New Delhi (cropped).jpg|thumb|Amit Shah takes oath with Ram Vilas Paswan beside him]]\nShah took oath as Cabinet Minister on 30 May 2019. He took office as [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]] on 1 June 2019.<ref>{{citation |title=PM Modi allocates portfolios. Full list of new ministers |url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/pm-modi-allocates-portfolios-full-list-of-new-ministers-1559288502067.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 May 2019 }}</ref> On 5 August 2019, Shah moved resolution to scrap Article 370 in the Rajya Sabha.,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kashmir-unrest-amit-shah-parliament-reservation-bill-amendment-artcle-370-1577275-2019-08-05|title=No Article 370 for Jammu & Kashmir, historic move by Modi govt|date=5 August 2019|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=5 August 2019}}</ref> and also reorganize the state with [[Jammu and Kashmir]] serving as one of the union territory and [[Ladakh]] region separated out as a separate union territory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/jammu-and-kashmir-crisis-live-updates-1564981600854.html|title=Jammu and Kashmir Live News: Article 370 to be revoked, J&K to be reorganised|date=5 August 2019|website=LiveMint}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2019, Shah declared in the Rajya Sabha of the Indian parliament that the [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC) will be implemented throughout the country.<ref name=\"Shah NRC IT\">{{cite news |title=Amit Shah: NRC to apply nationwide, no person of any religion should worry |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/amit-shah-nrc-rajya-sabha-1620810-2019-11-20 |accessdate=22 December 2019 |work=India Today |date=20 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, he introduced the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] bill, which grants Indian citizenship to religiously persecuted minority communities who migrated to the country before 2015 from the Muslim-majority countries of Pakistan, Bangladesh and Afghanistan. In [[North-East India]], people concerned about the impact of immigration on local culture and politics protested against the Act. Elsewhere, the opposition parties criticized the Act's exclusion of Muslims as detrimental to India's pluralism. Shah, however, insisted that that the bill was not anti-Muslim because it did not change the existing path to citizenship available for them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/india-parliament-passes-citizenship-bill-1.5392455 |title=India's parliament passes contentious citizenship bill |publisher=CBC News |date=20 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Electoral record ==\nSince 1989, Shah has fought 28 elections to various local bodies. As of 2019, he has never lost an election.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Year\n! Constituency\n! Result\n! Votes\n! % Votes\n! Source\n|-\n| [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]] ([[by-election]])\n| 1997\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 76,839\n| 56.10%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/ByeElection/ByeApril1997/S06/gj-64-la.html |title=Bye-Elections 1997: Sarkhej |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=27 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 1998\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 193,373\n| 69.81%\n| <ref name=\"rediff_1998_Sarkhej\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/election/gujarat/sarkhej.htm |title=Constituency Data - Summary: Sarkhej - 1998 |website=rediff.com |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2002 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 2002\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 288,327\n| 66.98%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/archive/Decse2002/pollupd/ac/states/s06/aconst64.htm |title=State Elections 2002: 64-Sarkhej Constituency of Gujarat |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2007 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 2007\n| [[Sarkhej]]\n| Won\n| 407,659\n| 68.00%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/archive/Dec2007/pollupd/ac/states/s06/aconst64.htm |title=State Elections 2007: 64-Sarkhej Constituency of Gujarat |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2012 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election|Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n| 2012\n| [[Naranpura (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Naranpura]]\n| Won\n| 103,988\n| 69.19%\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/ECI_Main/CI_2013/Gujaratl/45-Naranpura.pdf |title=Form-21E: 45-Naranpura |publisher=Election Commission of India |accessdate=26 June 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2019 Indian general election|General Election]]\n| 2019\n| [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]]\n| Won\n|888,210\n|69.76%\n|\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nShah is married to Sonal Shah and the couple have a son named [[Jay Shah|Jay]]. Shah was very close to his mother, who died from an illness on 8 June 2010.<ref name=\"Open_2014_Mind\"/><ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> People close to Shah have described him as someone who does not like to socialize much.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.asianage.com/india/shrewd-modi-loyalist-able-%E2%80%98manage-everything%E2%80%99-672 |title=Shrewd Modi loyalist able to 'manage everything' |author=Deepal Trivedi |date=23 July 2010 |newspaper=Asian Age }}</ref>  He has six sisters, two of whom live abroad in Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/report/ls-election-amit-shah-on-friday-wakes-up-late-eats-poha-chats-with-modi/20140516.htm|title=Exclusive! Amit Shah on Friday: Wakes up late, eats poha, chats with Modi|website=rediff.com|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> In September 2019, he  was successfully operated for lipoma at the backside of neck under local anaesthesia. After this minor surgery, he was  discharged.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/amit-shah-successfully-operated-for-lipoma-at-a-hospital-in-ahmedabad-5965286/ |title = Amit Shah undergoes operation for lipoma at Ahmedabad hospital|date = 5 September 2019}}</ref>\n== Controversies ==\n[[File:Prime Minister Narendra Modi visits Shauryanjali, a commemorative exhibition on the 1965 war.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Narendra Modi visits Shauryanjali, a commemorative exhibition on the 1965 war]]\nShah was accused of sidelining the police officers who testified against the Gujarat government in cases related to the fake encounters and the [[2002 Gujarat violence|2002 riots]]. Additional [[Director General of Police|DGP]] [[R. B. Sreekumar]], who gave evidence to the [[Nanavati-Shah commission]], was allegedly denied promotion. [[Rahul Sharma (Gujarat police)|Rahul Sharma]], who handed over phone records of police officers and politicians to the Commission, was charged with violating the [[Official Secrets Act]]. Additional DGP Kuldeep Sharma alleged that he had been moved from the police department to Gujarat State Sheep and Wool Development Corporation, after he accused Shah of taking a bribe of Rs 2.5 crore to bail out a conman who fraudulently withdrew Rs 1,600 crore from the Madhavpura Mercantile Cooperative Bank. Kuldeep Sharma was later made advisor to the central home ministry by the Congress government. His brother Pradeep Sharma was imprisoned in Gujarat from 2010 to 2011 on corruption charges. The brothers claim that the Gujarat Government was harassing them.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> Shah has also been accused of manipulating the electoral constituency delimitation exercise in Gujarat to favour BJP.<ref name=\"MM_2014_importance\"/>\n\nOn 11 December 2019 federal US commission on International Religious Freedom (USCIRF) asked the US administration to consider imposing sanctions against Home Minister Amit Shah if the Indian parliament passes the Citizenship Amendment Bill 2019. USCIRF in its statement said, \"CAB is a dangerous turn in the wrong direction; it runs counter to India\u2019s rich history of secular pluralism and the Indian Constitution, which guarantees equality before the law regardless of faith\". The commission chaired by Republican Tony Perkins said CAB \"enshrines a pathway to citizenship for immigrants that specifically excludes Muslims, setting a legal criterion for citizenship based on religion\". The external affairs ministry was quick in issuing a counter-statement in response to USCIRF by saying that it was not based on facts and the bill was to grant citizenship to persecuted religious minorities who arrived in India and does not aim to strip citizenship<ref name=\"Sanctions on Amit Shah\">{{cite web |last1=Amit Shah |first1=sanctions against |title=Sanctions against Amit Shah over CAB |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/sanctions-against-amit-shah-over-cab-rajnath-singh-jaishankar-may-take-up-issue-in-washington-dc/articleshow/72465942.cms |website=The Economic Times |publisher=The Economic Times |accessdate=8 March 2020 |ref=Amit Shah sanctions}}</ref>\n\n==== Snoopgate ====\nIn 2013, Shah was accused of having ordered illegal surveillance on a woman in 2009, during his tenure as a home minister. The investigative websites [[Cobrapost]] and Gulail released a set of taped audio conversations between Shah and police officer GL Singhal. The tapes had been submitted to the CBI in the [[Ishrat Jahan]] fake encounter case, and were leaked to these portals. The calls detail how the state machinery was used to surveil the woman and the IAS officer Pradeep Sharma (who was suspended by the Gujarat Government). Both Singhal and Shah repeatedly refer to a higher authority as ''Saheb'', believed to be the Chief Minister Narendra Modi.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cobrapost.com/index.php/news-detail?nid=3969&cid=23 |title=News Detail |publisher=Cobrapost.com |date= |accessdate=4 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231084530/http://www.cobrapost.com/index.php/news-detail?nid=3969&cid=23 |archive-date=31 December 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Shah denied all the accusations against him, calling them political propaganda by his opponents.<ref name=\"Caravan_Organiser_2014\"/> BJP's political opponents demanded a probe in this ''Snoopgate'' case. However, in May 2014, the woman approached the Supreme Court and stated that the surveillance on her was based on a \"personal request\", and she was thankful to the Gujarat government for ensuring her safety. She requested the court to block any investigation, stating that it would violate her privacy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/elections/article/election-2014/snoopgate-thankful-for-surveillance-woman-tells-supreme-court-519233 |title=Snoopgate: 'Thankful' for Surveillance, Woman Tells Supreme Court |author=Deepshikha Ghosh |date=6 May 2014 |publisher=NDTV }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.amitshah.co.in/ Official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[L. K. Advani]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Gandhinagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Gandhinagar]] |years=2019 \u2013 Present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rajnath Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=30 May 2019 \u2013 Present}}\n